m War US & Allied Combat Equipments|series=Elite 216|first=Gordon L.|last= Rottman |date=26 Jan 2017|isbn=9781472819055|publisher=Osprey Publishing|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Vietnam Armor in Action|first1=Gordon L.|last1= Rottman |first2=Donald|last2=Spaulding|date=2002|isbn=9789623616829|publisher= Concord Publications|series= Armor at War 7040|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Lee E.|last= Russell |title=Armies of the Vietnam War 2|series=Men at arms 143|publisher= Osprey Publishing |date=28 Jul 1983|isbn= 9780850455144|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=A Bright Shining Lie \u2013 John Paul Van and the American War in Vietnam|first=Neil|last=Sheehan|edition=ebook|publisher=Vintage|date=October 20, 2009|orig-year=September 12, 1988|isbn=978-0679724148|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Smith|first=Joseph E.|title=Small Arms of the World|url=https://archive.org/details/smallarmsofworld00smit|url-access=registration|edition =11|location=Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|publisher= The Stackpole Company|year=1969|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=US Combat Shotguns|series=Weapon 29|first=Leroy |last=Thompson|date=20 Aug 2013|isbn=9781780960142|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=vnGICwAAQBAJ|publisher=[[Osprey Publishing]]|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=MiG-17 and MiG-19 Units of the Vietnam War|series=Combat Aircraft 25|publisher=Osprey Publishing|first=Istv\u00e1n|last= Toperczer|date=25 Sep 2001|isbn=9781841761626|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Encyclopedia of the Vietnam War: A Political, Social, and Military History|edition=2nd |editor-first= Spencer C.|editor-last= Tucker|isbn=978-1-85109-960-3|date=May 2011|ref={{harvid|Tucker|2011}}}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Weapons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weapons Of The Vietnam War}}\n[[Category:Military equipment of the Vietnam War|*]]\n[[Category:Vietnam War-related lists]]\n[[Category:Vietnam War]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:National Firearms Museum, Vietnam-era rifles.jpg|thumb|Vietnam era rifles used by the US military and allies]]\nThis article is about the '''weapons used in the [[Vietnam War]]''', which involved the [[People's Army of Vietnam]] (PAVN) or North Vietnamese Army (NVA), National Liberation Front for South Vietnam (NLF) or [[Viet Cong]] (VC), and the armed forces of the [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam]] (ARVN), [[United States Armed Forces|United States]], [[Republic of Korea Armed Forces|Republic of Korea]], [[Armed Forces of the Philippines|Philippines]], [[Royal Thai Armed Forces|Thailand]], and the [[Australian Defence Force|Australian]], [[New Zealand Defence Force|New Zealand]] defence forces, and a variety of irregular troops.\n\nNearly all United States-allied forces were armed with U.S. weapons including the [[M1 Garand]], [[M1 carbine]], [[M14 rifle|M-14]] and [[M16 rifle|M-16]].  The Australian and New Zealand forces employed the 7.62&nbsp;mm [[L1A1 Self-Loading Rifle]] as their service rifle, with the occasional US M16.\n\nThe PAVN, although having inherited a variety of American, French, and Japanese weapons from [[World War II]] and the [[First Indochina War]] (aka French Indochina War), were largely armed and supplied by the [[People's Republic of China]], the [[Soviet Union]], and its [[Warsaw Pact]] allies. In addition, some weapons\u2014notably anti-personnel explosives, the [[K-50M]] (a [[PPSh-41]] copy), and \"home-made\" versions of the [[RPG-2]]\u2014were manufactured in North Vietnam. By 1969 the US Army had identified 40 rifle/carbine types, 22 machine gun types, 17 types of mortar, 20 recoilless rifle or rocket launcher types, nine types of antitank weapons, and 14 anti-aircraft artillery weapons used by ground troops on all sides. Also in use, primarily by anti-communist forces, were the 24 types of armored vehicles and self-propelled artillery, and 26 types of field artillery and rocket launchers.\n\n==Communist forces and weapons==\n[[File:Captured NVA Weapons.jpg|thumb|Captured PAVN weapons]]\nDuring the early stages of their insurgency, the Viet Cong mainly sustained itself with captured arms (often of American manufacture){{sfn|Sheehan|2009|p=813.3}} or crude, self-made weapons (e.g. copies of the US [[Thompson submachine gun]]{{sfn|Sheehan|2009|p=187.2}} and [[shotgun]]s made of galvanized pipes).{{sfn|Sheehan|2009|p=994.1}} Most arms were captured from poorly defended ARVN militia outposts.{{sfn|Sheehan|2009|p=814.4}}\n\nCommunist forces were principally armed with Chinese and Soviet weaponry though some VC guerrilla units were equipped with Western infantry weapons either captured from French stocks during the first Indochina war, such as the [[MAT-49]], or from ARVN units or requisitioned through illicit purchase.\n\nIn the summer and fall of 1967, all Viet Cong battalions were reequipped with arms of Soviet design such as the [[AK-47]] assault rifle and the [[RPG-2]] anti-tank weapon.{{sfn|Sheehan|2009|p=1883.5}} Their weapons were principally of Chinese<ref>{{cite web|first=Bob|last=Seals|url=http://www.militaryhistoryonline.com/20thcentury/articles/chinesesupport.aspx|title=Chinese Support for North Vietnam during the Vietnam War: The Decisive Edge|work=Military History Online|date=23 September 2008}}</ref> or Soviet manufacture.<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Albert|last=Parray|magazine=Military Review|url=http://calldp.leavenworth.army.mil/eng_mr/txts/VOL47/00000006/art2.pdf|title=Soviet aid to Vietnam|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110428210157/http://calldp.leavenworth.army.mil/eng_mr/txts/VOL47/00000006/art2.pdf|archive-date=28 April 2011|url-status=dead|date=June 1967}}</ref> The period up to the conventional phase in the 1970, the Viet Cong and NVA were primarily limited to mortars, recoil-less rifles and small-arms and had significantly lighter equipment and firepower in comparison with the US arsenal, relying on ambushes alongside superior stealth, planning, marksmanship and small-unit tactics to face the disproportionate US technological advantage.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=jexmAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT101|title=Indochina and Vietnam: The Thirty-five Year War, 1940\u20131975|last=Miller|first=Robert|last2=Wainstock|first2=Dennis D.|publisher=Enigma Books|year=2013|isbn=978-1936274666|location=|pages=101\u201302|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMany divisions within the NVA would incorporate armoured and mechanised battalions including the [[Type 59 tank]]., [[BTR-60]], [[D-74 122 mm field gun|Type 60 artillery]] and rapidly altered and integrated new war doctrines following the Tet Offensive into a mobile combined-arms force.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite web|url=http://www.historynet.com/north-vietnams-master-plan.htm|title=North Vietnam's Master Plan|website=HistoryNet|access-date=2018-06-01}}</ref> The North Vietnamese had both [[Amphibious vehicle|amphibious tanks]] (such as the [[PT-76]]) and [[light tank]]s (such the [[Type 62]]) used during the conventional phase. Experimental Soviet equipment started being used against ARVN forces at the same time, including [[Man-portable air-defense system]] [[9K32 Strela-2|SA-7 ''Grail'']] and [[anti-tank missile]]s including the [[9M14 Malyutka|AT-3 ''Sagger'']].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=IdRWAAAAQBAJ|title=Gi\u00e1p: The General Who Defeated America in Vietnam|last=Warren|first=James A.|publisher=St. Martin's Press|year=2013|isbn=978-1137098917}}</ref> By 1975 they had fully transformed from the strategy of mobile light-infantry and using the people's war concept used against the United States.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n==US weapons==\nThe American [[M16 rifle]] and [[XM177|XM177 carbine]], which both replaced the M14, was lighter and considered more accurate than the [[AK-47]] but was prone to malfunction. Often the gun suffered from a malfunction known as \"failure to extract\", which meant that the spent cartridge case remained lodged in the chamber after a round was fired. According to a congressional report, the malfunction was caused by a change of gunpowder in the ammunition, which was done without adequate testing and by a money saving policy, headed by Robert S. McNamara, to not issue adequate cleaning kits to soldiers. This led to a myth of a self-cleaning gun. These decisions were made without regard to the safety of soldiers and resulted in many deaths.\n\nThe heavily armored, 90&nbsp;mm gun [[M48 Patton|M48A3 'Patton' tank]] saw extensive action during the Vietnam War and over 600 were deployed with U.S. forces. They played an important role in infantry support though there were a  few tank versus tank battles. The [[M67 Flame Thrower Tank|M67A1 flamethrower tank]] (nicknamed the [[Zippo]]) was an M48 variant used in Vietnam. Artillery was used extensively by both sides but the Americans were able to ferry the lightweight 105&nbsp;mm [[M102 howitzer]] by helicopter to remote locations on quick notice.<ref>Bart Hagerman, USA Airborne: 50th Anniversary, Turner Publishing Company, p.237</ref><ref name=\"Tolsonarmy\">{{cite book |url = http://www.history.army.mil/books/vietnam/airmobility/airmobility-fm.html |title = Vietnam Studies: Airmobility 1961\u201371 |work = Department of the Army |author = Lieutenant General John J. Tolson |year = 1989 |publisher = US Government Printing Office| id = CMH Pub 90-4}}</ref> With its {{convert|17|mi|km|adj=on}} range, the Soviet [[130 mm towed field gun M1954 (M-46)|130 mm M-46 towed field gun]] was a highly regarded weapon and used to good effect by the PAVN. It was countered by the long-range, American 175&nbsp;mm [[M107 Self-Propelled Gun]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OWCNfR50jsc# |title=ITN news reel |work=Youtube |date=16 July 2007 |accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe United States had air superiority though many aircraft were lost to surface-to-air missiles and anti-aircraft artillery. U.S. airpower was credited with breaking the [[Battle of Khe Sanh|siege of Khe Sanh]] and blunting the 1972 [[Easter Offensive]] against South Vietnam. At sea, the U.S. Navy had the run of the coastline, using aircraft carriers as platforms for offshore strikes and other naval vessels for offshore artillery support. Offshore naval fire played a pivotal role in the [[Battle of Hu\u1ebf]] in February 1968, providing accurate fire in support of the U.S. counter-offensive to retake the city.<ref>{{cite book|first=George W.|last=Smith|title=The siege at Hue|publisher= Lynne Reinner Publishers|date=1999|pp=142-143}}</ref>\n[[File:Khu_tr\u01b0ng_b\u00e0y_m\u00e1y_bay.JPG|thumb|Captured South Vietnamese warplanes in Ho Chi Minh City]]\nThe Vietnam War was the first conflict that saw wide scale tactical deployment of helicopters.<ref>Dwayne A. Day, [http://www.centennialofflight.gov/essay/Rotary/Heli_at_War/HE14.htm Helicopters at War] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100414001319/http://www.centennialofflight.gov/essay/Rotary/Heli_at_War/HE14.htm |date=2010-04-14 }} U.S. Centennial of Flight Commission</ref> The [[Bell UH-1 Iroquois]] nicknamed \"Huey\" was used extensively in [[counter-guerilla]] operations both as a troop carrier and a gunship.<ref name=\"Tolsonarmy\" /> In the latter role it was outfitted with a variety of armaments including [[M60 machine gun]]s, multi-barreled 7.62&nbsp;mm [[Minigun]]s and unguided air-to-surface rockets.<ref name=\"Tolsonarmy\" /> The Hueys were also successfully used in [[MEDEVAC]] and search and rescue roles.<ref name=\"Tolsonarmy\" /> Two aircraft which were prominent in the war were the [[Lockheed AC-130|AC-130 \"Spectre\"]] Gunship and the [[UH-1]] \"Huey\" gunship. The AC-130 was a heavily armed [[Attack aircraft|ground-attack aircraft]] variant of the [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130 Hercules]] transport plane; it was used to provide [[close air support]], [[air interdiction]] and [[force protection]]. The AC-130H \"Spectre\" was armed with two 20&nbsp;mm [[M61 Vulcan]] cannons, one [[Bofors 40mm]] autocannon, and one 105&nbsp;mm [[M102 howitzer]]. The Huey is a [[military helicopter]] powered by a single, [[turboshaft]] engine, and approximately 7,000 UH-1 aircraft saw service in Vietnam. At their disposal ground forces had access to [[Boeing B-52 Stratofortress|B-52]] and [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4 Phantom II]] and others to launch [[napalm]], [[White phosphorus munitions|white phosphorus]], [[tear gas]] and [[chemical weapon]]s as well.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/24/opinion/vietnam-the-chemical-war.html?mtrref=www.google.ca&assetType=opinion|title=Opinion {{!}} Vietnam: The Chemical War|last=Biggs|first=David|access-date=2018-06-20|language=en}}</ref> The aircraft ordnance used during the war included [[precision-guided munition]], [[cluster bomb]]s, a [[thickening]]/[[Gelling agent|gelling]] agent generally mixed with petroleum or a similar fuel for use in an [[incendiary device]], initially against buildings and later primarily as an anti-personnel weapon that sticks to skin and can burn down to the bone.\n\nThe [[M18A1 Claymore Antipersonnel Mine|Claymore M18A1]], an anti-personnel mine was widely used, and is command-detonated and directional shooting 700 steel pellets in the [[kill zone]].\n\n==Weapons of the South Vietnamese, U.S., South Korean, Australian, and New Zealand Forces==\n\n===Hand combat weapons===\n[[File:KA-BAR.jpg|thumb|The KA-BAR knife was the most famous edged weapon of the war.]]\n* L1A1 and L1A2 bayonets - used on [[L1A1 Self-Loading Rifle]]{{sfn|Rottman|2017|p=39}}\n* [[M1905 bayonet]] - used on the M1 Garand.<ref name=\"M1 Vietnam\"/>\n* [[M1917 bayonet]] - used on various shotguns.{{sfn|Rottman|2017|p=39}}\n* [[M1 Bayonet]] - used on the M1 Garand.<ref name=\"M1 Vietnam\">{{cite web|title=The M1 Garand in Vietnam|date=17 January 2019 |website=wwiiafterwwii.wordpress.com|url=https://wwiiafterwwii.wordpress.com/2019/01/17/the-m1-garand-in-vietnam/}}</ref>\n* [[M3 fighting knife]]{{sfn|Rottman|2006|p=48}}\n* [[M4 bayonet]] - used on the M1 and M2 Carbine.{{sfn|Rottman|2017|p=39}}\n* [[M5 bayonet]] - used on the M1 Garand.{{sfn|Rottman|2017|p=39}}\n* [[M6 bayonet]] - used on the M14.{{sfn|Rottman|2017|p=39}}\n* [[M7 Bayonet]] - used on the M16.{{sfn|Rottman|2017|p=39}}\n* [[KA-BAR|Ka-Bar Utility/fighting Knife]] - used by the US Army, Navy and Marine Corps.{{sfn|Russell|1983|p=33}}{{sfn|Gilbert|2006|p=66}}\n* [[Gerber Mark II]] U.S. Armed Forces{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* [[Randall Made Knives]] - personally purchased by some US soldiers.{{sfn|Russell|1983|p=37}}\n* M1905,M1917,M1 and [[Lee Enfield]] bayonets cut down and converted in to fighting knives.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n* [[Bow and arrow|Bow]] - used by [[Mobile Riverine Force|US Mobile Riverine Force]].<ref name=\"Bow\">{{cite web|title=Archery in Vietnam|url=https://www.3riversarchery.com/blog/archery-in-vietnam/}}{{better source needed|date=December 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Crossbow]] - used by South Vietnamese [[Degar|Montagnards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Montagnard Crossbow, Vietnam|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/C364947|website=awm.gov.au|publisher=[[Australian War Memorial]]|access-date=4 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Pistols and revolvers===\n* [[M1911 pistol|Colt M1911A1]] \u2013 standard US and ARVN sidearm.{{sfn|Ezell|1988|p=155}}{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=45}}\n* [[Browning Hi-Power]] \u2013 used by Australian and New Zealand forces (L9 pistol).{{sfn|Rottman|2017|p=11}} Also used on an unofficial basis by US reconnaissance and Special Forces units.{{sfn|Rottman 2011b|p=40}}\n* [[Colt Model 1903 Pocket Hammerless]] \u2013 carried by US military officers. Replaced by the Colt Commander in the mid-1960s{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* [[Colt Detective Special]] - .38 Special revolver, used by some ARVN officers{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=45}}\n* [[Colt Police Positive Special]] - .38 Special revolver, used by USAF and [[tunnel rat]]s{{sfn|Rottman|2012|p=22}} \n* [[High Standard HDM]] \u2013 Integrally suppressed .22LR handgun, supplemented by the Mark 22 Mod 0 in the later stages of the war.<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>\n* [[Ingram MAC-10]] \u2013 automatic pistol used by US special operations forces.<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>\n* [[Luger pistol|Luger P08]] - CIA provided pistol{{sfn|Rottman|2002|p=43}}\n* [[M1917 revolver]] \u2013 .45 ACP revolver{{sfn|Rottman|2002|p=21}} used by the South Vietnamese and US forces during the beginning of the war alongside the [[Smith & Wesson Model 10]]. Used rather prominently by  tunnel rats.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* [[Smith & Wesson Model 29#Quiet Special Purpose Revolver|Quiet Special Purpose Revolver]] - 40. revolver used by tunnel rats.\n* [[Smith & Wesson Model 10]] \u2013 .38 Special revolver used by ARVN,{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=47}} by US Army and USAF pilots{{sfn|Rottman|2008|p=56}} and by tunnel rats{{sfn|Rottman|2012|p=22}}\n* [[Smith & Wesson Model 12]] \u2013 .38 Special revolver carried by US Army and USAF pilots.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* [[Smith & Wesson Model 15]] \u2013 .38 Special revolver carried by USAF Security Police Units.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* [[Smith & Wesson Model 27]] \u2013 .357 Magnum revolver carried by [[MACV-SOG|MACVSOG]].{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* [[Smith & Wesson Model 39|Smith & Wesson Mark 22 Mod.0 \"Hush Puppy\"]] \u2013 Suppressed pistol used by [[United States Navy SEALs|US Navy SEALs]] and other U.S. special operations forces.<ref name=\"Dockery\">{{cite book |last=Dockery|first=Kevin|title=Weapons of the Navy SEALs|date=December 2004|publisher=Berkley Publishing Group|location=[[New York City]]|isbn=0-425-19834-0|page=382}}</ref>\n* [[Walther P38]] - CIA provided pistol{{sfn|Rottman|2002|p=43}}\n\n===Infantry rifles===\n[[File:ARVN Rangers defend Saigon, Tet Offensive.jpg|thumb|[[Vietnamese Rangers]] with [[M16 rifle|M16 rifles]] in [[Saigon]] during the [[T\u1ebft Offensive]]]]\n* [[L1A1 Self-Loading Rifle]] \u2013 used by Australian and New Zealand soldiers in Vietnam{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=975}}\n[[File:JunctionCity1967SupplyDrop.jpg|thumb|A U.S. soldier with an [[M14 rifle|M14]] watches as supplies are dropped in [[Vietnam]], 1967.]]\n* [[M1 Garand]] \u2013 used by the South Vietnamese{{sfn|Ezell|1988|pp=51-52}} and South Koreans{{sfn|Russell|1983|p=34}}\n* [[M1 Carbine|M1, M1A1, & M2 Carbine]] \u2013 used by the South Vietnamese Military, Police and Security Forces,{{sfn|Ezell|1988|pp=51-52}} South Koreans,{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=973}} U.S. military, and Laotians supplied by the U.S.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Female South Vietnamese Popular Force members on patrol in B\u1ebfn C\u00e1t District.JPEG|thumb|South Vietnamese [[People's Self-Defense Force]] militiawomen with [[M1 carbine|M1 carbines]]]]\n* [[M14 rifle]] - issued to most U.S. troops from the early stages of the war until 1967\u201368, when it was replaced by the M16.{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=973}}\n* [[M16 rifle|M16, XM16E1, and M16A1]] \u2013 M16 was issued in 1964, but due to reliability issues, it was replaced by the M16A1 in 1967 which added the forward assist and chrome-lined barrel to the rifle for increased reliability.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanrifleman.org/articles/us-m16/|title=U.S. M16: A Half-Century of America's Combat Rifle|website=www.americanrifleman.org}}</ref>\n* [[CAR-15#CAR-15 Commando (XM177/GAU-5 series)|CAR-15]] \u2013 carbine variant of the M16 produced in very limited numbers, fielded by special operations early on. Later supplemented by the improved XM177.\n* [[CAR-15#CAR-15 Commando (XM177/GAU-5 series)|XM177 (Colt Commando)/GAU-5]] \u2013 further development of the CAR-15, used heavily by [[MACV-SOG]], the US Air Force, and US Army.<ref name=\"Dockery\"/> \n* [[Stoner 63]] \u2013 used by US Navy SEALs and USMC.<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>\n* T223 \u2013 a copy of the [[Heckler & Koch HK33]]  built under license by [[Harrington & Richardson]] used in small numbers by SEAL teams. Even though the empty H&R T223 was 0.9 pounds (0.41&nbsp;kg) heavier than an empty M16A1, the weapon had a forty-round magazine available for it and this made it attractive to the SEALS.<ref name=\"Dockery\"/> \n* [[MAS-36 rifle]] - used by South Vietnamese militias{{sfn|Smith|1969|p=720}}\n* [[AK-47]], [[AKM]] and [[Type 56]] - Captured rifles were used by South Vietnamese{{sfn|Rottman|2010|page=18}} and U.S forces.{{sfn|Rottman 2011b|p=38}}{{sfn|Rottman|2007b|p=48}}\n* [[G3 rifle]] - Used by the Green Berets.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Sniper/marksman rifles===\n* [[M1 Garand|M1C/D Garand and MC52]] - used by CIA advisors, the USMC and the US Navy early in the war.{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=974}}<ref name=\"Sniping\">{{cite book|title=Sniper Rifles: From the 19th to the 21st Century|series=Weapon 6|first=Martin|last= Pegler|date=20 Nov 2010|isbn=9781849083980|publisher=Osprey Publishing|pages=56\u201359}}</ref> Approximately 520 were supplied to the ARVN and 460 to the Thai forces.<ref>{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Leroy|title=The M1 Garand|publisher=Osprey|year=2012|location=Oxford|pages=67\u201368|isbn=9781849086219|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k-C6CwAAQBAJ|ref=harv}}</ref>\n* [[M1903 Springfield|M1903A4 Springfield]] \u2013 used by the USMC early in the war, replaced by the M40.<ref name=\"Sniping\"/>\n* [[M21 Sniper Weapon System]] \u2013 sniper variant of the M14 rifle used by the US Army.{{sfn|Tucker|2011|pp=974-975}}\n* [[M40 rifle|M40]] ([[Remington Model 700]])\u2013 bolt-action sniper rifle meant to replace the M1903A4 Springfield rifle and Winchester Model 70; used by the USMC<ref name=\"Sniping\"/>\n* [[Parker-Hale M82]] - used by ANZAC forces{{sfn|Rottman|2017|p=11}}\n* [[Winchester Model 70]] \u2013 used by the USMC<ref name=\"Sniping\"/>\n* [[Mosin Nagant]] - used by South Vietnamese militias{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Submachine guns===\n* [[Beretta M12]] \u2013 limited numbers were used by [[Embassy of the United States, Saigon|U.S. Embassy]] security units.<ref name = \"Gander\">{{cite book|last = Gander| first = Jerry| title = Jane's Infantry Weapons 2002\u20132003 | publisher = Jane's Information Group| year = 2002| isbn =0-7106-2434-4 | pages =214, 899\u2013906}}</ref>\n* [[Carl Gustav M/45]] \u2013 used by Navy SEALs in the beginning of the war, but later replaced by the [[Smith & Wesson M76]] in the late 1960s. Significant numbers were also utilized by the South Vietnamese,<ref name=\"Dockery\"/> and limited numbers were used in Laos by advisors, and Laotian fighters.\n* [[Smith & Wesson M76]] \u2013 copy of the Carl Gustav M/45. Few were actually shipped to Navy SEALs fighting in Vietnam.{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=1076}}\n* [[F1 submachine gun]] \u2013 replaced the Owen Gun in Australian service.{{sfn|Rottman 2011a|p=20}}<ref name=\"Sterling\">{{cite book|title=The Sterling Submachine Gun|series=Weapon 65|first= Matthew |last=Moss |date=29 Nov 2018|isbn=9781472828088 |publisher=Osprey Publishing|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=_i1tDwAAQBAJ|page=65}}</ref>\n* [[M3 submachine gun|M3 Grease gun]] \u2013 standard U.S. military submachine gun, also used by the South Vietnamese<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>{{sfn|Rottman|2002|p=41}}\n* [[M50 Reising|M50/55 Reising]] \u2013 limited numbers were used by MACVSOG and other irregular forces.<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>\n* [[Madsen M-50]] \u2013 used by South Vietnamese forces, supplied by the CIA.{{sfn|Rottman|2002|p=41}}\n* [[MAS-38]] submachine gun - used by South Vietnamese militias.{{sfn|Dye|Laemlein|2015|p=22}}\n* [[MAT-49]] submachine gun \u2013 used by South Vietnamese militias.{{sfn|Smith|1969|p=720}} Captured models were used in limited numbers<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>\n* [[MP 40]] submachine gun - used by South Vietnamese forces, supplied by the CIA.{{sfn|Rottman|2002|p=41}}\n* [[Owen Gun]] \u2013 standard Australian submachine-gun in the early stages of the war, later replaced by the F1.{{sfn|Rottman 2011a|p=20}}<ref name=\"Sterling\"/>\n* [[Sten submachine gun]] \u2013 used by US special operations forces, often with a suppressor mounted.{{sfn|Rottman 2011b|p=38}}\n* [[Sterling submachine gun]] \u2013 used by Australian [[Special Air Service Regiment]] and other special operations units.<ref name=\"Sterling\"/>\n* [[Thompson submachine gun]] \u2013 used often by South Vietnamese troops, and in small quantities by US artillery and helicopter units. \n* [[Uzi]] \u2013 used by special operations forces and some South Vietnamese, supplied from Israel.{{sfn|Rottman 2011b|p=38}}\n* [[MP5]] - used by the Green Berets, including the MP5SD variant.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Shotguns===\n[[File:Ithaca 37.jpg|thumb|[[Ithaca 37]]]]\nShotguns were used as an individual weapon during jungle patrol; infantry units were authorized a shotgun by TO&E (Table of Organization & Equipment). Shotguns were not general issue to all infantrymen, but were select issue weapons, such as one per squad, etc.\n\n* [[Ithaca 37]] \u2013 pump-action shotgun used by the United States and ARVN.<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>{{sfn|Thompson|2013|p=19}}\n* [[Remington Model 10]] \u2013 pump-action shotgun used by the United States.{{sfn|Dye|Laemlein|2015|pp=33-35&38}}\n* [[Remington Model 11-48]] - semi-automatic shotgun used by US Army.{{sfn|Rottman|2002|p=42}}\n* [[Remington Model 31]] \u2013 pump-action shotgun used by the US Army, the SEALs and the ARVN.{{sfn|Rottman|2002|p=42}}{{sfn|Dye|Laemlein|2015|pp=34-37}}\n* [[Remington Model 870]] \u2013 pump-action shotgun primary shotgun used by Marines, Army and Navy after 1966.<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>{{sfn|Rottman|2002|p=42}}{{sfn|Thompson|2013|p=65}}\n* [[Remington 1100|Remington 7188]] \u2013 experimental select fire shotgun, withdrawn due to lack of reliability. Used by US Navy SEALs<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>{{sfn|Thompson|2013|pp=25-26}}\n* [[Savage Model 69E]] - pump-action shotgun used by the US Army.{{sfn|Rottman|2008|p=56}}\n* [[Browning Auto-5|Savage Model 720]] - semi-automatic shotgun.{{sfn|Dye|Laemlein|2015|p=39}}\n* [[Stevens Model 77E]] \u2013 pump-action shotgun used by Army and Marine forces. Almost 70,000 Model 77Es were procured by the military for use in SE Asia during the 1960s.{{sfn|Thompson|2013|p=20}} Also very popular with the ARVN because of its small size.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Canfield|first= Bruce N. |title=Combat Shotguns of the Vietnam War|magazine=[[American Rifleman]]|date=March 2002 |pages=44\u201347&92\u201395|url=https://www.americanrifleman.org/articles/2016/4/22/combat-shotguns-of-the-vietnam-war/}}</ref>\n* [[Stevens Model 520/620]]{{sfn|Thompson|2013|p=19}}\n* [[Winchester Model 1912]] - used by USMC.{{sfn|Higgins|2015|p=24}}\n* [[Winchester Model 1200]] \u2013 pump-action shotgun used by the US Army.{{sfn|Thompson|2013|pp=20-21}}\n* [[Winchester Model 1897]] \u2013 used by the Marines during the early stages of the war.{{sfn|Thompson|2013|p=7}}\n\n===Machine guns===\n* [[M60 machine gun]] \u2013 standard [[General-purpose machine gun]] for US, ANZAC, and ARVN forces throughout the war.{{sfn|Rottman 2011a|p=20}}\n[[File:Marine M-60 machine gun team fighting in the Citadel.jpg|thumb|US Marine fires his M60 machine gun at an enemy position during the [[Battle of Hu\u1ebf]].]]\n* [[Colt Machine Gun]] \u2013 experimental light machine gun deployed by SEAL Team 2 in 1970.<ref name=\"Dockery\"/> \n* [[M1918 Browning Automatic Rifle]] \u2013 used by the ARVN during the early stages of the war,{{sfn|Ezell|1988|p=60}} as well as many that were airdropped into Laos and used by Laotian fighters.\n* [[FM 24/29 light machine gun]] - used by South Vietnamese militias{{sfn|Smith|1969|p=720}} \n* [[RPD machine gun]] (and Type 56) - captured and used by reconnaissance teams of Mobile Strike Forces, MAC-V-SOG and other special operation forces. Also commonly modified, a common modification was to cut down the barrel.{{sfn|Rottman|2007b|p=48}}\n* [[Stoner 63|Stoner M63A Commando & Mark 23 Mod.0]] \u2013 used by Navy SEALs and tested by [[Force Recon]].<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>\n* [[Minigun|M134 Minigun]] - 7.62&nbsp;mm vehicle mounted machine gun (rare){{sfn|Rottman 2011c|p=38}}\n* [[M1917 Browning machine gun]] \u2013 .30cal heavy machine gun issued to the ARVN and also in limited use by the U.S. Army.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* [[M1919 Browning machine gun]] (and variants such as M37) \u2013 vehicle mounted machine gun.{{sfn|Rottman|Spaulding|2002|p=4}} Meanwhile, still of use by many South Vietnamese infantry.{{sfn|Rottman|2017|p=11}}\n* [[M73 machine gun]] \u2013 tank mounted machine gun.{{sfn|Rottman|Spaulding|2002|p=4}}\n* [[MG3 machine gun|MG1]] - used by the Green Berets{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n* [[M2 Browning|Browning M2HB .50cal Heavy Machine Gun]]<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>\n\n===Grenades and mines===\n[[File:M18 Claymore Mine.jpg|thumb|Claymore anti-personnel mine in use in Vietnam]]\n* [[AN-M8 smoke grenade|AN-M8]] - white smoke grenade{{sfn|Rottman|2015|p=56}}{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=451}}\n* [[C-4 (explosive)|C4]] explosive{{sfn|Rottman|2006|p=45}}\n* [[Mk 2 grenade|Mark 2 fragmentation grenade]]{{sfn|Rottman|2015|p=26}}\n* [[M1 smoke pot]]{{sfn|Rottman|2006|p=45}}\n* [[M26 grenade|M26 fragmentation grenade]] and many subvariants{{sfn|Russell|1983|p=9}}{{sfn|Rottman|2015|pp=56-57}}\n* [[M67 grenade|M59 and M67 fragmentation grenade]]{{sfn|Rottman|2015|p=28}}{{sfn|Russell|1983|p=9,36}}\n* [[United States hand grenades#M6/A1, M7/A1/A2/A3 and M54|M6/M7-series riot control grenades]]{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=451}} - Used to clear NVA/VC out of caves, tunnels and buildings<ref name=smoke>{{cite web|url=http://www.modernforces.com/uniform_smoke.htm|title=Smoke Grenades|website=MACV-SOG \u2013 Living History}}</ref> or stop a pursuer.{{sfn|Rottman|2015|p=56}}\n* [[United States hand grenades#M14 TH3|AN/M14 TH3 thermite grenade]] - Incendiary grenade used to destroy equipment and as a fire-starting device.{{sfn|Rottman|2015|p=56}}\n* [[United States hand grenades#M15, M16, and M34|M15 and M34 smoke grenades]] - filled with white phosphorus,{{sfn|Russell|1983|p=37}} which ignites on contact with air and creates thick white smoke.{{sfn|Rottman|2015|p=56}} Used for signalling and screening purposes, as well as an anti-personnel weapon in enclosed spaces, as the burning white phosphorus would rapidly consume any oxygen, suffocating the victims.\n* [[M18 grenade Smoke Hand Grenade]] - Signaling/screening grenade available in red, yellow, green, and purple.{{sfn|Russell|1983|p=30}}{{sfn|Rottman|2015|p=56}}\n* [[V40 Mini-Grenade]]{{sfn|Rottman|2015|p=29}}\n* [[OF 37 grenade]] and [[DF 37 grenade]], French grenades used by the ARVN in the 1950s{{sfn|Rottman|2009|p=43}}{{sfn|Rottman|2015|p=18}}\n* [[United States hand grenades#XM58|XM58 riot control grenade]] - A miniature riot control grenade used by MACVSOG and Navy SEALs.<ref name=smoke/>\n* [[M14 mine]] - anti-personnel blast mine{{sfn|Russell|1983|p=37}}\n* [[M15 mine]] - anti-tank mine{{sfn|Rottman|2005|p=17}}\n* [[M16 mine]] - bounding anti-personnel fragmentation mine{{sfn|Rottman|2005|p=17}}\n* [[M18A1 Claymore Antipersonnel Mine|M18/M18A1 Claymore]] - command-detonated directional anti-personnel mine{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=45}}{{sfn|Rottman 2011b|p=43}}\n* [[M19 mine]] - anti-tank mine{{sfn|Rottman|2005|p=17}}\n\n===Grenade and Rocket Launchers===\n* [[M1 grenade adapter|M1/M2 rifle grenade adapters]] - used to convert a standard fragmentation grenade (M1) or smoke grenade (M2) into a rifle grenade in conjunction with the M7 grenade launcher.\n* [[M7 grenade launcher|M7 and M8 rifle grenade launcher]] - rifle grenade launcher used with respectively the M1 Garand and the M1 carbine, used by the South Vietnamese. Could fire the [[M9 rifle grenade|M9]] and [[M17 rifle grenade]]s.{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=430}}\n* [[M31 HEAT rifle grenade]] \u2013 Used primarily by the U.S. Army before the introduction of the M72 LAW. Fired from the M1 Garand and M14 Rifle.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n*[[M79 grenade launcher|M79 Grenade Launcher]] - primary U.S. grenade launcher used by all branches of the US military, as well as ANZAC forces and the ARVN.<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=430}}\n* [[China Lake Grenade Launcher]] - pump action weapon used in very small numbers.<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>\n*[[XM148 grenade launcher|XM148]] - experimental underbarrel 40mm grenade launcher that could be attached to the M16 rifle or XM177 carbine. Withdrawn due to safety reasons.<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=430}}\n* [[M203 grenade launcher]] - single-shot 40mm underslung grenade launcher designed to attach to a M16 rifle (or XM177 carbine, with modifications to the launcher). First tested in combat April 1969.<ref name=\"Dockery\"/>{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=430}}\n* [[Mk 18 Mod 0 grenade launcher|Mark 18 Mod 0 grenade launcher]] - Hand-cranked, belt-fed, 40x46mm grenade launcher used by the US Navy.<ref name=\"Stoner\">{{cite web|last=Stoner|first= Bob |url=http://www.warboats.org/mst2bremmer/stoner_ord_notes/stonerhtml/Stoners_ord_notes.htm|title=Ordnance Notes|website=warboats.org}}</ref>\n*[[Mk 19 grenade launcher|Mark 19 grenade launcher]] - Automatic, belt-fed, 46x53mm grenade launcher.<ref name=\"Stoner\"/>\n* [[Mk 20 Mod 0 grenade launcher]] - Automatic, belt-fed, 40x46mm grenade launcher. Primarily used by riverine crews but also used by Air Force Special Operations.<ref name=\"Stoner\"/>\n* [[XM174 grenade launcher]] - Automatic, belt-fed, 40x46mm grenade launcher used mainly by the US Army.{{sfn|Ezell|1988|pp=106-107}}\n* [[Bazooka]] - The M9 variant was supplied to the ARVN during the early years of the war,{{sfn|Rottman|2010|pp=7, 34}} while the M20 \"Super Bazooka\" was used by the USMC and the ARVN until the full introduction of the M67 90mm recoilless rifle and of the M72 LAW.<ref>{{cite book |last=Rottman |first=Gordon L. |date=2012 |title=The Bazooka |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dae6CwAAQBAJ |location= |publisher=Osprey Publishing |pages= 69\u201370, 75\u201376|isbn=978-1849088015 |author-link= |ref=harv}}</ref>\n* [[M72 LAW]] \u2013 66mm anti-tank rocket launcher.{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=987}}\n* [[M202 FLASH|XM202]] - experimental four-shot 66mm incendiary rocket launcher.<ref>{{cite report|title=XM191 Multishot Portable Flame Weapon|url=https://apps.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/868942.pdf|pages=2\u20133|year=1970|publisher=Army Concept Team in Vietnam}}</ref>\n* [[FIM-43 Redeye]] [[Man-portable air-defense system|MANPADS (Man-Portable Air-Defence System)]] \u2013 shoulder-fired heat-seeking anti-air missile, used by the US Army and USMC.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* [[BGM-71 TOW]]  -  wire-guided anti-tank missile{{sfn|McKenna|2011|p=91}}\n\n===Flamethrowers===\n* [[M2 flamethrower|M2A1-7 and M9A1-7 flamethrowers]]{{sfn|Rottman|2012|p=24}}{{sfn|Gilbert|2006|p=67}}\n\n===Infantry support weapons===\n[[File:My Tho, Vietnam. A Viet Cong base camp being. In the foreground is Private First Class Raymond Rumpa, St Paul, Minnesota - NARA - 530621 edit.jpg|thumb|A US soldier carries an [[M67 recoilless rifle|M67 recoilless]] rifle past a burning [[Viet Cong]] base camp in [[M\u1ef9 Tho]], [[South Vietnam]], 1968]]\n* [[M18 recoilless rifle]] - 57mm shoulder-fired/tripod mounted recoilless rifle, used by the ARVN early in the war.{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=35}}\n* [[M20 recoilless rifle]] - 75mm tripod/vehicle-mounted recoilless rifle, used by US and ARVN forces early in the war.{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=7}}\n* [[M67 recoilless rifle]] - 90mm shoulder-fired anti-tank recoilless rifle, used by the US Army, US Marine Corps, ANZAC and ARVN selected forces.{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=7}}{{sfn|Ezell|1988|p=143}}{{sfn|Rottman 2011a|p=22}}\n* [[M40 recoilless rifle]] 106mm tripod/vehicle-mounted recoilless rifle.{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=7}}{{sfn|Ezell|1988|p=143}}\n* [[M2 mortar]] - 60mm mortar, used in conjunction with the lighter but less accurate and lower-range M19 mortar.{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=15}}\n* [[M19 mortar]] - 60mm mortar, used in conjunction with the older, heavier M2 mortar.{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=15}}{{sfn|Higgins|2015|p=78}}\n*[[Brandt Mle 27/31]] - 81mm mortar, used by ARVN forces{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=9}}\n*[[M1 mortar]] - 81mm mortar, used by ARVN forces.{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=9}}\n* [[M29 mortar]] - 81mm mortar, used by US and ARVN forces.{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=9}}{{sfn|Rottman|2007a|p=56}}\n* [[L16 81mm mortar|L16A1 mortar]] - 81mm, used by ANZAC forces.{{sfn|Rottman 2011a|p=20}}\n* [[82-BM-37]] - captured 82mm mortar, few used by USMC with US rounds.{{sfn|Rottman|2005|p=44}}\n* [[M30 107 mm Mortar|M30 mortar]] 107mm mortar, used by US and ARVN forces.{{sfn|Rottman|2010|p=32}}{{sfn|Rottman|2008|p=56}}\n** M98 Howtar, variant of the latter mounted on a [[M116 howitzer]] carriage.{{sfn|Gilbert|2006|pp=68-69}}\n\n===Artillery===\n[[File:Self-propelled-howitzer-vietnam.jpg|thumb|[[Self-propelled artillery|Self-propelled]] [[M109 howitzer|Howitzer M109]] in Vietnam]]\n* [[M45 Quadmount|M55 quad machine gun]] - used to defend US Army bases and on vehicles{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=71}}{{sfn|Rottman 2011c|p=36}}\n* [[Oerlikon 20 mm cannon]] - used on riverine crafts{{sfn|Robinson|1983|p=136}}\n* [[Bofors 40 mm gun]] - used on riverine crafts{{sfn|Robinson|1983|p=136}}\n* [[M101 howitzer|105 mm Howitzer M101A1/M2A1]]{{sfn|Higgins|2015|p=28}}{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=71}}\n* [[M102 howitzer|105 mm Howitzer M102]]{{sfn|Foster|2007|pp=8, 25}}{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=71}}\n* [[M114 155 mm howitzer|155 mm Howitzer M114]]{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=71}}{{sfn|Foster|2007|pp=25, 28}}\n* [[M53 155mm Self-Propelled Gun|M53]] Self-propelled 155mm gun{{sfn|Green|1996|p=71}}\n* [[M55 Self Propelled Howitzer|M55]] Self-propelled 8-inch howitzer{{sfn|Green|1996|p=71}}\n* [[M107 self-propelled gun|M107]] Self-propelled 175mm gun{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=71}}{{sfn|Foster|2007|p=14}}{{sfn|Green|1996|p=72}}\n* [[M108 howitzer|M108]] Self-propelled 105&nbsp;mm howitzer{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=71}}\n* [[M109 howitzer|M109]] Self-propelled 155&nbsp;mm howitzer{{sfn|Dunstan|1985|p=38}}\n* [[M110 howitzer|M110]] Self-propelled 8-inch howitzer{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=71}}{{sfn|Foster|2007|p=14}}\n* [[M116 howitzer|75mm Pack Howitzer M1]]{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* [[OTO Melara Mod 56|L5 pack howitzer]] 105&nbsp;mm pack howitzer used by Australia<ref>{{cite web|title= L5 105mm Pack Howitzer|website=5rar.asn.au|url=http://www.5rar.asn.au/gallery/103-battery1.htm}}</ref> and New Zealand<ref name=\"NZ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.armymuseum.co.nz/blog/gunners-day-feature-italian-l5-105mm-pack-howitzer.html|publisher=National Army Museum|title=Gunners\u2019 Day Feature: Italian L5 105mm Pack Howitzer|website=armymuseum.co.nz|date=26 May 2017}}</ref>\n* [[MIM-23 Hawk]] - medium-range surface to air missile used in very small quantities by the US Marines.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b4291974;view=1up;seq=389 Use of Hawk Missiles in Vietnam]. // Department of Defense appropriations for 1970, pt. 5, pp. 377-378.</ref>\n\n====Artillery ammunition types====\n* HE ([[Explosive#High explosives|High Explosive]]) - standard artillery round.{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=72}}\n* [[High-explosive anti-tank warhead|High-explosive anti-tank round]] - fired by 105mm guns.{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=72}}\n* [[White phosphorus munitions|White phosphorus]] - used for screening or incendiary purposes.{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=72}}\n* [[Shell (projectile)#Smoke|Smoke shells]] - used for screening.{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=72}}\n* [[Airborne leaflet propaganda|Leaflet shell]] - rarely used.{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=72}}\n* [[Beehive anti-personnel round|Beehive flechette rounds]] - antipersonnel rounds.{{sfn|Tucker|2011|pp=72-73}}\n* [[Dual-Purpose Improved Conventional Munition|Improved Conventional Munition]] - antipersonnel shell with sub-munitions.{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=73}}\n\n===Aircraft===\n(listed alphabetically by modified/basic mission code, then numerically in ascending order by design number/series letter)\n* [[Douglas A-1 Skyraider|A-1 Skyraider]] - ground attack aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=44-47}}\n* [[A-3 Skywarrior]] - carrier-based bomber{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=56-59}}\n* [[Douglas A-4 Skyhawk|A-4 Skyhawk]] - carrier-based strike aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=108-111}}\n* [[Grumman A-6 Intruder|A-6 Intruder]] - carrier-based all weather strike aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=68-69}}\n* [[LTV A-7 Corsair II|A-7 Corsair II]] - carrier-based strike aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=156-157}}\n* [[A-26 Invader]] - light bomber{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=48-49}}\n* [[Cessna A-37 Dragonfly|A-37 Dragonfly]] - ground attack aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=36-37}}\n* [[Douglas AC-47 Spooky|AC-47 Spooky]] - gunship{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=50-53}}\n* [[Fairchild AC-119|AC-119G \"Shadow\"]] - gunship{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=60-61}}\n* [[Fairchild AC-119|AC-119K \"Stinger\"]] - gunship{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=60-61}}\n* [[Lockheed AC-130|AC-130 \"Spectre\"]] - gunship{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=84-89}}\n* [[Fairchild AU-23 Peacemaker|AU-23 Peacemaker]] - ground attack aircraft{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* [[Helio AU-24 Stallion|AU-24 Stallion]] - ground attack aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|2001|p=412}}\n* [[Boeing B-52 Stratofortress|B-52 Stratofortress]] - heavy bomber{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=22-27}}\n* [[Martin B-57 Canberra|B-57 Canberra]] - medium bomber{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=100-105}}\n* [[English Electric Canberra|Canberra B.20]] - [[Royal Australian Air Force]] medium bomber{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=100-105}}\n* [[Grumman C-1 Trader|C-1 Trader]] - cargo/transport aircraft\n* [[Grumman C-2 Greyhound|C-2 Greyhound]] - cargo/transport aircraft\n* [[Lockheed C-5 Galaxy|C-5 Galaxy]] - strategic lift cargo aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=82-83}}\n* [[de Havilland Canada DHC-4 Caribou|C-7 Caribou]] - tactical cargo aircraft, used by the U.S. Air Force, the Royal Australian Air Force and the South Vietnamese Air Force{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=42-43}}\n* [[Curtiss C-46 Commando|C-46 Commando]] - cargo/transport aircraft{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=20}}\n* [[Douglas C-47 Skytrain|C-47]] - cargo/transport aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=50-53}}\n* [[Douglas C-54 Skymaster|C-54]] - transport aircraft{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=20}}\n* [[Boeing C-97 Stratofreighter|C-97 Stratofreighter]] - cargo/transport aircraft{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* [[Fairchild C-119 Flying Boxcar|C-119 Boxcar]] - cargo/transport aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=60-61}}\n* [[Lockheed C-121 Constellation|C-121 Constellation]] - transport aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=92-93}}\n* [[C-123 Provider]] - cargo/transport aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=62-65}}\n* [[Douglas C-124 Globemaster II|C-124 Globemaster II]] - cargo/transport aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=56-57}}\n* [[C-130 Hercules]] - cargo/transport plane{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=84-89}}\n* [[Douglas C-133 Cargomaster|C-133 Cargomaster]] - cargo/transport aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=54-55}}\n* [[Lockheed C-141 Starlifter|C-141 Starlifter]] - strategic cargo aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=90-91}}\n* [[Grumman E-1 Tracer|E-1 Tracer]] - carrier-based airborne early warning (AEW) aircraft{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=27}}\n* [[Northrop Grumman E-2 Hawkeye|E-2 Hawkeye]] - carrier-based airborne early warning (AEW) aircraft{{sfn|Tucker|2011|p=27}}\n* [[A-3 Skywarrior|EA-3 Skywarrior]] - carrier-based tactical electronic reconnaissance aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=56-59}}\n* [[Northrop Grumman EA-6B Prowler|EA-6B Prowler]] - carrier-based electronic warfare & attack aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=68-69}}\n* [[Martin B-57 Canberra|EB-57 Canberra]] - tactical electronic reconnaissance aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=100-105}}\n* [[B-66 Destroyer|EB-66]] - tactical electronic reconnaissance aircraft{{sfn|Nalty|Watson|Neufeld|1981|pp=56-59}