{"title_page": "Hoy", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox Scottish island\n|Image=Old man of hoy2.jpg\n|ImageCaption=The [[Old Man of Hoy]], at the western side of the island, seen from the south\n|location_map = Scotland Orkney\n|caption=Hoy shown within Orkney\n|coordinates = {{coord|58.83|-3.3|display=inline}}\n|GridReference=ND263961\n|celtic name=\n|norse name=H\u00e1-\u00f8y<ref name =Smith>{{Haswell-Smith|344-6}}</ref>\n|meaning of name= Old Norse for 'high island'<ref name =Smith/>\n|area=  {{cvt|14318|ha|sqmi|frac=16}}<ref name =Smith/>\n|area rank=12\n|highest elevation= [[Ward Hill, Hoy|Ward Hill]], {{cvt|479|m|ft|0}}\n|Population=419<ref name=NRS>{{NRS1C}}</ref>{{refn|Including South Walls.|group=Note}}\n|population rank=23\n|population density ={{cvt|2.9|PD/km2}}<ref name=Smith/><ref name=NRS/>\n|main settlement=[[Lyness]]\n|island group=[[The Mainland, Orkney|Orkney]]\n|local authority=[[Orkney|Orkney Islands]]\n|references=<ref name =Smith/><ref>[http://www.orkneyjar.com/placenames/pl-isle.htm Orkney Placenames]. Orkneyjar.</ref><ref name=OS6>{{cite map|title=Ordnance Survey: Landranger map sheet 6 ''Orkney (Mainland)''|ISBN=9780319228128|publisher=Ordnance Survey|date=2014}}</ref>\n<ref>Anderson, Joseph (Ed.) (1893) ''Orkneyinga Saga''. Translated by J\u00f3n A. Hjaltalin & Gilbert Goudie. Edinburgh. James Thin and Mercat Press (1990 reprint). {{ISBN|0-901824-25-9}}</ref><ref name=Pedersen>Pedersen, Roy (January 1992) ''Orkneyjar ok Katanes'' (map, Inverness, Nevis Print)</ref>\n}}\n'''Hoy''' (from [[Old Norse language|Norse]] ''H\u00e1ey'' meaning \"high island\") is an island in [[Orkney]], Scotland, measuring {{convert|143|km2|sqmi|0}} &mdash; ranked largest in the [[archipelago]] after [[Orkney Mainland|Mainland]].  A natural causeway, ''the Ayre'', links to much smaller [[South Walls]]; the two islands are treated as one entity by the UK census.<ref name=NRS/><ref>{{GRO10}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Dwarfie Stane, Hoy - geograph.org.uk - 71967.jpg|thumb|left|The Dwarfie Stane]]The [[Dwarfie Stane|Dwafile Stane]] (as pictured left) lies in the north of the Rackwick valley and dates back to around 5000 BCE however it is thought the chamber was carved out sometime between the [[Neolithic]] and the Early [[Bronze Age]]. It is unique in northern [[Europe]], bearing similarity to [[Neolithic]] or [[Bronze Age]] tombs around the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]. The tomb has a small rectangular entrance and cleft, hence its name.{{refn|Dwarfie/dwarfy is an adjective of a slightly deprecated term for any small grown human, [[dwarfism|dwarf]]; stane is the word stone before the [[Great English Vowel Shift]] as in most Roman roads locally or collectively recorded as [[Stane Street (disambiguation)|\"stane streets\"]]<!--intentional link to DAB page-->.|group=Note}}Basing their dates on similar tombs found in the Mediterranean, archaeologists have settled on a date of around 3,000 BC.and is first evidence of human habitation on Hoy.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.orkneyjar.com/history/tombs/dwarfiestane/index.html|title=Orkneyjar - The Dwarfie Stane, Hoy|website=www.orkneyjar.com|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Discoveries have been made on the mainland of [[Orkney]] at the [[Ness of Brodgar]] that date back as early as 3510 BCE with the first stone circle in the British Isles found there.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=McKie|first=Robin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/oct/06/orkney-temple-centre-ancient-britain|title=Neolithic discovery: why Orkney is the centre of ancient Britain|date=2012-10-06|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref>\n\nThe two most northerly [[Martello tower|Martello Towers]] in the UK stand here, built in 1814 to defend merchant shipping in the natural harbour of [[Longhope, Orkney|Longhope]] against [[Privateer|privateers]] commissioned by American president Madison, who declared war in 1812. Arguably, an effective deterrent as there is no record of them ever being engaged in serious combat.\n\n=== '''Modern History''' ===\nAlthough the population of Hoy is now only around 400, there was a much larger population in the past. In 1890 there were 4 schools on the island and 4 churches suggesting a much larger population. Despite the larger population there was no paved road between the north of the island and the southern tip of the island and [[South Walls]] island, only a footpath. There was however an unmetalled road between the two villages on the north of the isle; Rackwick and Moaness. <ref name=\":2\">observations of ordnance survey maps of the time.</ref>\n\n==== '''Longhope lifeboat station''' ====\nA Lifeboat has been on Hoy since 1874 which was originally housed in a prominent stone building close to the west end of the causeway that links the two islands of Hoy and South Walls together at a cost of \u00a3228. It was stationed there as it meant that the lifeboat could be dragged over wooden skids and into the sea in either North Bay, giving access to [[Scapa Flow]] or in Aith Hope, an offshoot of the notorious [[Pentland Firth]] to the south. The shed continued to serve as the base of the Longhope lifeboat until 1906, when it was replaced.\n\nThe lifeboat station that stands slightly to the south of the original station which is now home to the Longhope Lifeboat Museum, cost \u00a32,700 to build in 1906. It continued to serve as the base for the Longhope lifeboat until 1999. Whilst based at this station,1969 On 17 March the lifeboat 'T.G.B.' ON 962, capsized while on service to the Liberian vessel 'Irene' and her entire crew of eight lost their lives, known as the Longhope lifeboat disaster.<ref name=\":2\" /> In August of that year an Arun-class lifeboat, Sir Max Aitken II became the Longhope lifeboat. This class was designed to stay permanently afloat, and the decision was taken to move her to purpose-built moorings at Longhope pier. The lifeboats that have served here since have also been stationed at Longhope, including the current vessel the Helen Comrie (a [[Tamar-class lifeboat|Tamar class lifeboat)]] and her predecessor The Queen Mother, which was based here between 2004 and 2006. A station has been built where the lifeboat is moored at Longhope which is also the main habout for boats to and from the island. <ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== '''World Wars''' ====\nThe main naval base for the British fleet in both the [[World War I|First]] and [[World War II|Second]] World Wars, [[Scapa Flow]], was at [[Lyness]] in the southeast of the island. This iis because the sheltered harbour offered an ideal location for refuelling and maintaining the fleet.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe sheltered sounds around the islands of [[Flotta]], Fara, Cava and [[Rysa Little]] made up the [[Royal Navy|Royal Navy\u2019s]] main fleet anchorage in [[Scapa Flow]] during both world wars. At Lyness on Hoy, an oil depot, naval quarters and stores were established during [[World War I]] and were considerably developed in the second world war to form the [[Scapa Flow]] Naval Base Headquarters, temporary wartime home to thousands of military and civilian personnel.\n\nNear the modern ferry terminal is a solitary oil storage tank and pumping station, which together now serve as the Scapa Flow Visitor Centre. This tank, which had a capacity of 12 000 tons, was one of four erected in 1917 when oil-fired warships were coming into service with the Royal Navy. The associated pumping station, also built in 1917, housed the steam pumps which drew the heavy fuel oil from tankers at the pier. Originally coal fired, the pumps were converted to diesel power in 1936 when, with the threat of another war looming, plans were laid to massively increase oil-storage capacity. In 1937, Messrs Balfour Beatty & Co. Ltd were contracted to build 12 slightly larger 15 000 [[ton]] tanks, bringing the total complement of above-ground tanks to 16 by 1938. Also in 1937 the considerable engineering challenge of creating underground tanks \u2013 safer from potential aerial attack \u2013 went to [[Sir William Arrol & Co.|Sir William Arrol & Co. Ltd]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/98128/hoy-lyness-royal-naval-oil-terminal|title=Hoy, Lyness, Royal Naval Oil Terminal {{!}} Canmore|website=canmore.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nDuring the early years of [[World War II|WWII]], up to 12,000 personnel were based in and around [[Lyness]] to support the defences of the naval anchorage at [[Scapa Flow]] and the ships that used it. To support this huge population, hundreds of accommodation huts were built in a number of camps around [[Lyness]]. A large [[wharf]] was built (known as the Golden Wharf because of its huge cost) along with a series of piers and slipways. Offices, workshops, stores and recreational buildings were erected, including a cinema, a theatre and several churches. An earlier headquarters building was replaced in 1943 by an imposing concrete HQ and communications centre, also located high on Wee Fea which now serves as a hotel.\n\nLyness was finally closed as a naval base in 1957, when it was cleared of many of its wartime buildings, but continued to function as an Admiralty oil fuel depot until 1977.\n[[File:Lyness Royal Naval Cemetery, Hoy, Orkney - geograph.org.uk - 121041.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Lyness%20Royal%20Naval%20Cemetery,%20Hoy,%20Orkney%20-%20geograph.org.uk%20-%20121041.jpg|thumb|Lyness Royal Naval Cemetery.]]\nLyness Royal Naval Cemetery is situated around 1.0km inland from the naval base and has an area of around 10,000 square meters (2.5 acres). The cemetery was begun in 1915 when [[Scapa Flow]] was the base of the [[Grand Fleet]]. [[Lyness]] remained as a [[Royal Navy|Royal Naval]] base until July 1946 and the cemetery contains graves from both wars. There are 445 [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] burials of the First World War, 109 of which are unidentified. The majority of the graves are of officers, ratings, and members of the land forces lost from H.M.S. \"[[HMS Hampshire (1903)|Hampshire]],\" \"[[HMS Vanguard|Vanguard]],\" \"[[HMS Narborough (1916)|Narborough]]\" and \"[[HMS Opal (1915)|Opal]].\" The 200 burials of the Second World War in the cemetery include those of 26 men from H.M.S. \"Royal Oak\", which was sunk off [[Longhope, Orkney|Longhope]] in Scapa Flow by a [[German U-boat]] on 14 October 1939. 8 of these burials are unidentified. The cemetery also contains the graves of 14 sailors of the [[German Navy]] (the [[High Seas Fleet]] was interned at [[Scapa Flow]] after the [[Armistice of 11 November 1918|1918 Armistice]]), 3 German airmen and 1 German sailor from the 1939-45 war and 1 Norwegian sailor of the 1939-45 war. There are also 30 civilian burials in the site (mostly [[Merchant Navy (United Kingdom)|Merchant Navy seaman]]).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/74567/LYNESS%20ROYAL%20NAVAL%20CEMETERY|title=Cemetery|website=www.cwgc.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nHoy is probably most famous though for the stack of the Rackwick coast; the [[Old Man of Hoy]] a sea stack formed from [[Old Red Sandstone]], it is one of the tallest stacks in the United Kingdom at a height of 449-foot (137-metres). The Old Man is popular with climbers, and was first climbed in 1966. Created by the erosion of a cliff through [[hydraulic action]] some time after 1750, the stack is no more than a few hundred years old, and paintings 1817 shows the stack with an arch at the bottom which has now further eroded and no longer remains hence it may soon collapse into the sea.\n\nThe dramatic coastline of Hoy can be seen by visitors travelling to Orkney by ferry from the Scottish mainland. It has some of the highest sea cliffs in the Uk at St John's Head, which reach 350m (1,150ft)<ref name=\"Smith\" />\n\nThe name Hoy comes from the [[Old Norse language|Norse]] word ''H\u00e1ey'' meaning \"high island\". It is therefore not surprising that the island of Hoy is the most mountainous in the [[Orkney]] [[archipelago]]. The highest point on the island (and indeed the whole archipelago is [[Ward Hill, Hoy|Ward Hill]] which stands at 481 m (1,578 ft) and is to the north of the island. There is a [[Triangulation station|trig point]] at the summit. \n\nHoy is part of the [[Hoy and West Mainland National Scenic Area|Hoy and West Mainland]] [[National Scenic Area (Scotland)|National Scenic Area]], one of 40 in Scotland.<ref>[http://www.snh.gov.uk/protecting-scotlands-nature/protected-areas/national-designations/nsa/ National Scenic Areas] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311014235/http://www.snh.gov.uk/protecting-scotlands-nature/protected-areas/national-designations/nsa/|date=11 March 2017}}. SNH. Retrieved 30 March 2011</ref>\n\nPatches of northernmost scattered, hardy woodland and the remote possibility of locally extant [[Orkney charr]] (''[[Salvelinus inframundus]]'') documented in 1908 at Heldale Water.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/135414/4126169|title=The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref> \n\n== Transport ==\nThere is evidence that there was at one point an airfield on Hoy, possibly due to its connections with the navy. There are two suggested sites both on [[South Walls]], one on the southern coast (Snelsetter) which opened in August 1934 and was closed at the end of [[World War II|World War Two]]. It was used by military and civil aircraft, and now is open land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abct.org.uk/airfields/airfield-finder/snelsetter-hoy/|title=Snelsetter (Hoy) - Airfields of Britain Conservation Trust UK|website=www.abct.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Another just east of the [[causeway]] that links the two islands of Hoy and [[South Walls]]. Which opened in November 1972 and closed in 1993. It was used by civilian aircraft solely and was operated by the airline [[Loganair]] it is also now open land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abct.org.uk/airfields/airfield-finder/hoy-longhope/|title=Hoy (Longhope) - Airfields of Britain Conservation Trust UK|website=www.abct.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The first flight to a nearby island of [[Flotta]] on 1 March 1977 was recorded to have landed a Hoy. Both airfields are now disused.  \n\n[[Orkney Ferries]] traverse the west of Scapa Flow with two routes:\n\n*Lyness on Hoy and [[Longhope, Orkney|Longhope]] on associated Walls via small [[Flotta]] to/from the village of [[Houton]] on [[Orkney Mainland]]. \n*Moaness in Hoy via small [[Graemsay]] to/from the town of [[Stromness]] on Orkney Mainland.\n\nThere is a community bus on Hoy that runs the east coast road (between Moness and Longhope). During the summer months a mini bus runs between the Moness harbour and Rackwick hostel.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n== Mythology ==\nIn [[Norse mythology]], Hoy hosted [[Hja\u00f0ningav\u00edg]], the never-ending battle between He\u00f0in and H\u00f6gni.\n\n==Wildlife==\nHoy is an [[Important Bird Area]].<ref>[http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/sitefactsheet.php?id=2495 Important Bird Areas factsheet: Hoy] Birdlife.org, Retrieved 24 January 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.globalspecies.org/birdareas/display/2495 Hoy IBA] Global Species.org, Retrieved 24 January 2015</ref>\nThe northern part of the island is an [[RSPB]] [[nature reserve|reserve]] due to its importance for birdlife, particularly [[great skua]]s and [[red-throated diver]]s. It was sold to the RSPB by the Hoy Trust for a nominal amount.<ref name=\"haswell-smith\">{{Cite book|last=Haswell-Smith|first=Hamish|title=The Scottish Islands|year=1996|publisher=Canongate|isbn=0-86241-579-9|page=283}}</ref>\n''[[Anastrepta orcadensis]]'',  a [[Marchantiophyta|liverwort]] also known as Orkney Notchwort, was first discovered on Ward Hill by [[William Jackson Hooker]] in 1808.<ref name=RBGE>[http://www.rbge.org.uk/science/cryptogamic-plants-and-fungi/bryology \"Bryology (mosses, liverworts and hornworts)\"] Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh. Retrieved 15 May 2008.</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/stream/annalsofscottish16edin/annalsofscottish16edin_djvu.txt \"West Highland Mosses And Problems They Suggest\"] (January 1907) ''Annals Of Scottish Natural History'' '''61''' p. 46. Edinburgh. Retrieved 11 June 2008.</ref>\n\nThe northern and western parts of Hoy, along with much of the adjoining sea area, is designated as a [[Special Protection Area]]<ref name=sitelink>{{cite web|url=http://gateway.snh.gov.uk/sitelink/searchmap.jsp |title=Sitelink - Map Search |publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|accessdate=2018-01-24}}</ref> due to its importance for nine breeding bird species: [[arctic skua]], [[fulmar]], [[great black-backed gull]], [[great skua]], [[Common murre|guillemot]], [[Black-legged kittiwake]], [[peregrine falcon]], [[Atlantic puffin|puffin]] and [[red-throated diver]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://gateway.snh.gov.uk/sitelink/siteinfo.jsp?pa_code=8513| title=Site Details for Hoy (SPA)|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=2018-03-05|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref> The area is important for its seabird assemblage, which regularly supports 120,000 individual seabirds during the breeding season.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=1902| title=SPA Description (Hoy)|publisher=Joint Nature Conservation Committee|date=2005-07-21|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nHoy is featured prominently in the 1984 video for \"[[Here Comes The Rain Again]]\" by [[Eurythmics]].\n\nHoy also has a performing arts theatre, the Gable End Theatre, which opened in 2000 and has a capacity of 75. The theatre is managed by the Hoy and Walls drama community.\n\nSome rather incongruous [[Art Deco]] structures nearby date from this period. The [[Arts and Crafts Movement|Arts and Crafts]] architect [[William Lethaby]] rebuilt Melsetter house for mountaineer [[Thomas Middlemore]] at the end of the nineteenth century leaving untouched the adjacent barn which is probably mid-18th century.<ref name=\"Tinniswood\">{{cite book|last=Tinniswood|first=Adrian|url=https://books.google.com/books?q=thomas+middlemore++1896++sold+&btnG=Search+Books|title=The Arts & Crafts House|publisher=[[Watson-Guptill Publications]]|year=1999|isbn=0-8230-0364-7|location=New York|pages=34\u201337|authorlink=Adrian Tinniswood}}</ref><ref name=\"Historic Scotland\">{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB48367|desc=Walls (Hoy), Melsetter, The Hall, including Gatepiers to West|cat=B|access-date=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Hoy Cliffs.jpg| Cliffs on the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] coast of Hoy, south of Rackwick\nFile:ScapaFlowVisitorCentreRLH.jpg| Scapa Flow Visitor Centre\nFile:PicHoyHigh.jpg| Hoy High Lighthouse on Graemsay, viewed from Mainland\nFile:Hoy_Orkney_Landesinnere.JPG|Rackwick Valley\nFile:Hoy Orkney Southside.jpg|Rackwick\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Scottish islands}}\n* [[List of islands of Scotland]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hoy}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n*[http://www.hoyorkney.com/ Island of Hoy website launched December 2008]\n*[http://www.readingmountaineeringclub.org.uk/images/Hoy/image5.htm Old Man of Hoy picture gallery]\n\n{{Coord|58|51|N|3|18|W|region:GB_type:isle|display=title}}\n\n{{South West Orkney}}\n{{Orkney Islands}}\n{{Islands of Scotland}}\n{{NSAs in Scotland}}\n{{RSPB sites in Scotland}}\n\n[[Category:Hoy| ]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Orkney Islands]]\n[[Category:Important Bird Areas of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Locations in Norse mythology]]\n[[Category:National scenic areas of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Orkney]]\n[[Category:Royal Society for the Protection of Birds reserves in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox Scottish island\n|Image=Old man of hoy2.jpg\n|ImageCaption=The [[Old Man of Hoy]], at the western side of the island, seen from the south\n|location_map = Scotland Orkney\n|caption=Hoy shown within Orkney\n|coordinates = {{coord|58.83|-3.3|display=inline}}\n|GridReference=ND263961\n|celtic name=\n|norse name=H\u00e1-\u00f8y<ref name =Smith>{{Haswell-Smith|344-6}}</ref>\n|meaning of name= Old Norse for 'high island'<ref name =Smith/>\n|area=  {{cvt|14318|ha|sqmi|frac=16}}<ref name =Smith/>\n|area rank=12\n|highest elevation= [[Ward Hill, Hoy|Ward Hill]], {{cvt|479|m|ft|0}}\n|Population=419<ref name=NRS>{{NRS1C}}</ref>{{refn|Including South Walls.|group=Note}}\n|population rank=23\n|population density ={{cvt|2.9|PD/km2}}<ref name=Smith/><ref name=NRS/>\n|main settlement=[[Lyness]]\n|island group=[[The Mainland, Orkney|Orkney]]\n|local authority=[[Orkney|Orkney Islands]]\n|references=<ref name =Smith/><ref>[http://www.orkneyjar.com/placenames/pl-isle.htm Orkney Placenames]. Orkneyjar.</ref><ref name=OS6>{{cite map|title=Ordnance Survey: Landranger map sheet 6 ''Orkney (Mainland)''|ISBN=9780319228128|publisher=Ordnance Survey|date=2014}}</ref>\n<ref>Anderson, Joseph (Ed.) (1893) ''Orkneyinga Saga''. Translated by J\u00f3n A. Hjaltalin & Gilbert Goudie. Edinburgh. James Thin and Mercat Press (1990 reprint). {{ISBN|0-901824-25-9}}</ref><ref name=Pedersen>Pedersen, Roy (January 1992) ''Orkneyjar ok Katanes'' (map, Inverness, Nevis Print)</ref>\n}}\n'''Hoy''' (from [[Old Norse language|Norse]] ''H\u00e1ey'' meaning \"high island\") is an island in [[Orkney]], Scotland, measuring {{convert|143|km2|sqmi|0}} &mdash; ranked largest in the [[archipelago]] after [[Orkney Mainland|Mainland]].  A natural causeway, ''the Ayre'', links to much smaller [[South Walls]]; the two islands are treated as one entity by the UK census.<ref name=NRS/><ref>{{GRO10}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Dwarfie Stane, Hoy - geograph.org.uk - 71967.jpg|thumb|left|The Dwarfie Stane]]The [[Dwarfie Stane|Dwafile Stane]] (as pictured left) lies in the north of the Rackwick valley and dates back to around 5000 BCE however it is thought the chamber was carved out sometime between the [[Neolithic]] and the Early [[Bronze Age]]. It is unique in northern [[Europe]], bearing similarity to [[Neolithic]] or [[Bronze Age]] tombs around the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]. The tomb has a small rectangular entrance and cleft, hence its name.{{refn|Dwarfie/dwarfy is an adjective of a slightly deprecated term for any small grown human, [[dwarfism|dwarf]]; stane is the word stone before the [[Great English Vowel Shift]] as in most Roman roads locally or collectively recorded as [[Stane Street (disambiguation)|\"stane streets\"]]<!--intentional link to DAB page-->.|group=Note}}Basing their dates on similar tombs found in the Mediterranean, archaeologists have settled on a date of around 3,000 BC.and is first evidence of human habitation on Hoy.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.orkneyjar.com/history/tombs/dwarfiestane/index.html|title=Orkneyjar - The Dwarfie Stane, Hoy|website=www.orkneyjar.com|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Discoveries have been made on the mainland of [[Orkney]] at the [[Ness of Brodgar]] that date back as early as 3510 BCE with the first stone circle in the British Isles found there.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=McKie|first=Robin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/oct/06/orkney-temple-centre-ancient-britain|title=Neolithic discovery: why Orkney is the centre of ancient Britain|date=2012-10-06|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref>\n\nThe two most northerly [[Martello tower|Martello Towers]] in the UK stand here, built in 1814 to defend merchant shipping in the natural harbour of [[Longhope, Orkney|Longhope]] against [[Privateer|privateers]] commissioned by American president Madison, who declared war in 1812. Arguably, an effective deterrent as there is no record of them ever being engaged in serious combat.\n\n=== '''Modern History''' ===\nAlthough the population of Hoy is now only around 400, there was a much larger population in the past. In 1890 there were 4 schools on the island and 4 churches suggesting a much larger population. Despite the larger population there was no paved road between the north of the island and the southern tip of the island and [[South Walls]] island, only a footpath. There was however an unmetalled road between the two villages on the north of the isle; Rackwick and Moaness. <ref name=\":2\">observations of ordnance survey maps of the time.</ref>\n\n==== '''Longhope lifeboat station''' ====\nA Lifeboat has been on Hoy since 1874 which was originally housed in a prominent stone building close to the west end of the causeway that links the two islands of Hoy and South Walls together at a cost of \u00a3228. It was stationed there as it meant that the lifeboat could be dragged over wooden skids and into the sea in either North Bay, giving access to [[Scapa Flow]] or in Aith Hope, an offshoot of the notorious [[Pentland Firth]] to the south. The shed continued to serve as the base of the Longhope lifeboat until 1906, when it was replaced.\n\nThe lifeboat station that stands slightly to the south of the original station which is now home to the Longhope Lifeboat Museum, cost \u00a32,700 to build in 1906. It continued to serve as the base for the Longhope lifeboat until 1999. Whilst based at this station,1969 On 17 March the lifeboat 'T.G.B.' ON 962, capsized while on service to the Liberian vessel 'Irene' and her entire crew of eight lost their lives, known as the Longhope lifeboat disaster.<ref name=\":2\" /> In August of that year an Arun-class lifeboat, Sir Max Aitken II became the Longhope lifeboat. This class was designed to stay permanently afloat, and the decision was taken to move her to purpose-built moorings at Longhope pier. The lifeboats that have served here since have also been stationed at Longhope, including the current vessel the Helen Comrie (a [[Tamar-class lifeboat|Tamar class lifeboat)]] and her predecessor The Queen Mother, which was based here between 2004 and 2006. A station has been built where the lifeboat is moored at Longhope which is also the main habout for boats to and from the island. <ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== '''World Wars''' ====\nThe main naval base for the British fleet in both the [[World War I|First]] and [[World War II|Second]] World Wars, [[Scapa Flow]], was at [[Lyness]] in the southeast of the island. This iis because the sheltered harbour offered an ideal location for refuelling and maintaining the fleet.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe sheltered sounds around the islands of [[Flotta]], Fara, Cava and [[Rysa Little]] made up the [[Royal Navy|Royal Navy\u2019s]] main fleet anchorage in [[Scapa Flow]] during both world wars. At Lyness on Hoy, an oil depot, naval quarters and stores were established during [[World War I]] and were considerably developed in the second world war to form the [[Scapa Flow]] Naval Base Headquarters, temporary wartime home to thousands of military and civilian personnel.\n\nNear the modern ferry terminal is a solitary oil storage tank and pumping station, which together now serve as the Scapa Flow Visitor Centre. This tank, which had a capacity of 12 000 tons, was one of four erected in 1917 when oil-fired warships were coming into service with the Royal Navy. The associated pumping station, also built in 1917, housed the steam pumps which drew the heavy fuel oil from tankers at the pier. Originally coal fired, the pumps were converted to diesel power in 1936 when, with the threat of another war looming, plans were laid to massively increase oil-storage capacity. In 1937, Messrs Balfour Beatty & Co. Ltd were contracted to build 12 slightly larger 15 000 [[ton]] tanks, bringing the total complement of above-ground tanks to 16 by 1938. Also in 1937 the considerable engineering challenge of creating underground tanks \u2013 safer from potential aerial attack \u2013 went to [[Sir William Arrol & Co.|Sir William Arrol & Co. Ltd]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/98128/hoy-lyness-royal-naval-oil-terminal|title=Hoy, Lyness, Royal Naval Oil Terminal {{!}} Canmore|website=canmore.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nDuring the early years of [[World War II|WWII]], up to 12,000 personnel were based in and around [[Lyness]] to support the defences of the naval anchorage at [[Scapa Flow]] and the ships that used it. To support this huge population, hundreds of accommodation huts were built in a number of camps around [[Lyness]]. A large [[wharf]] was built (known as the Golden Wharf because of its huge cost) along with a series of piers and slipways. Offices, workshops, stores and recreational buildings were erected, including a cinema, a theatre and several churches. An earlier headquarters building was replaced in 1943 by an imposing concrete HQ and communications centre, also located high on Wee Fea which now serves as a hotel.\n\nLyness was finally closed as a naval base in 1957, when it was cleared of many of its wartime buildings, but continued to function as an Admiralty oil fuel depot until 1977.\n[[File:Lyness Royal Naval Cemetery, Hoy, Orkney - geograph.org.uk - 121041.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Lyness%20Royal%20Naval%20Cemetery,%20Hoy,%20Orkney%20-%20geograph.org.uk%20-%20121041.jpg|thumb|Lyness Royal Naval Cemetery.]]\nLyness Royal Naval Cemetery is situated around 1.0km inland from the naval base and has an area of around 10,000 square meters (2.5 acres). The cemetery was begun in 1915 when [[Scapa Flow]] was the base of the [[Grand Fleet]]. [[Lyness]] remained as a [[Royal Navy|Royal Naval]] base until July 1946 and the cemetery contains graves from both wars. There are 445 [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] burials of the First World War, 109 of which are unidentified. The majority of the graves are of officers, ratings, and members of the land forces lost from H.M.S. \"[[HMS Hampshire (1903)|Hampshire]],\" \"[[HMS Vanguard|Vanguard]],\" \"[[HMS Narborough (1916)|Narborough]]\" and \"[[HMS Opal (1915)|Opal]].\" The 200 burials of the Second World War in the cemetery include those of 26 men from H.M.S. \"Royal Oak\", which was sunk off [[Longhope, Orkney|Longhope]] in Scapa Flow by a [[German U-boat]] on 14 October 1939. 8 of these burials are unidentified. The cemetery also contains the graves of 14 sailors of the [[German Navy]] (the [[High Seas Fleet]] was interned at [[Scapa Flow]] after the [[Armistice of 11 November 1918|1918 Armistice]]), 3 German airmen and 1 German sailor from the 1939-45 war and 1 Norwegian sailor of the 1939-45 war. There are also 30 civilian burials in the site (mostly [[Merchant Navy (United Kingdom)|Merchant Navy seaman]]).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/74567/LYNESS%20ROYAL%20NAVAL%20CEMETERY|title=Cemetery|website=www.cwgc.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nHoy is probably most famous though for the stack of the Rackwick coast; the [[Old Man of Hoy]] a sea stack formed from [[Old Red Sandstone]], it is one of the tallest stacks in the United Kingdom at a height of 449-foot (137-metres). The Old Man is popular with climbers, and was first climbed in 1966. Created by the erosion of a cliff through [[hydraulic action]] some time after 1750, the stack is no more than a few hundred years old, and paintings 1817 shows the stack with an arch at the bottom which has now further eroded and no longer remains hence it may soon collapse into the sea.\n\nThe dramatic coastline of Hoy can be seen by visitors travelling to Orkney by ferry from the Scottish mainland. It has some of the highest sea cliffs in the Uk at St John's Head, which reach 350m (1,150ft)<ref name=\"Smith\" />\n\nThe name Hoy comes from the [[Old Norse language|Norse]] word ''H\u00e1ey'' meaning \"high island\". It is therefore not surprising that the island of Hoy is the most mountainous in the [[Orkney]] [[archipelago]]. The highest point on the island (and indeed the whole archipelago is [[Ward Hill, Hoy|Ward Hill]] which stands at 481 m (1,578 ft) and is to the north of the island. There is a [[Triangulation station|trig point]] at the summit. \n\nHoy is part of the [[Hoy and West Mainland National Scenic Area|Hoy and West Mainland]] [[National Scenic Area (Scotland)|National Scenic Area]], one of 40 in Scotland.<ref>[http://www.snh.gov.uk/protecting-scotlands-nature/protected-areas/national-designations/nsa/ National Scenic Areas] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311014235/http://www.snh.gov.uk/protecting-scotlands-nature/protected-areas/national-designations/nsa/|date=11 March 2017}}. SNH. Retrieved 30 March 2011</ref>\n\nPatches of northernmost scattered, hardy woodland and the remote possibility of locally extant [[Orkney charr]] (''[[Salvelinus inframundus]]'') documented in 1908 at Heldale Water.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/135414/4126169|title=The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref> \n\n== Transport ==\nThere is evidence that there was at one point an airfield on Hoy, possibly due to its connections with the navy. There are two suggested sites both on [[South Walls]], one on the southern coast (Snelsetter) which opened in August 1934 and was closed at the end of [[World War II|World War Two]]. It was used by the military and civil aircrafts,and now is open land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abct.org.uk/airfields/airfield-finder/snelsetter-hoy/|title=Snelsetter (Hoy) - Airfields of Britain Conservation Trust UK|website=www.abct.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Another just east of the [[causeway]] that links the two islands of Hoy and [[South Walls]]. Which opened in November 1972 and closed in 1993. It was used by civilian aircraft soley and was operated by the airline [[Loganair]] it is also now open land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abct.org.uk/airfields/airfield-finder/hoy-longhope/|title=Hoy (Longhope) - Airfields of Britain Conservation Trust UK|website=www.abct.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The first flight to a nearby island of [[Flotta]] on 1 March 1977 was recorded to have landed a Hoy. Both airfields are now disused.  \n\n[[Orkney Ferries]] traverse the west of Scapa Flow with two routes:\n\n*Lyness on Hoy and [[Longhope, Orkney|Longhope]] on associated Walls via small [[Flotta]] to/from the village of [[Houton]] on [[Orkney Mainland]]. \n*Moaness in Hoy via small [[Graemsay]] to/from the town of [[Stromness]] on Orkney Mainland.\n\nThere is a community bus on Hoy that runs the east coast road (between Moness and Longhope). During the summer months a mini bus runs between the Moness harbour and Rackwick hostel.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n== Mythology ==\nIn [[Norse mythology]], Hoy hosted [[Hja\u00f0ningav\u00edg]], the never-ending battle between He\u00f0in and H\u00f6gni.\n\n==Wildlife==\nHoy is an [[Important Bird Area]].<ref>[http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/sitefactsheet.php?id=2495 Important Bird Areas factsheet: Hoy] Birdlife.org, Retrieved 24 January 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.globalspecies.org/birdareas/display/2495 Hoy IBA] Global Species.org, Retrieved 24 January 2015</ref>\nThe northern part of the island is an [[RSPB]] [[nature reserve|reserve]] due to its importance for birdlife, particularly [[great skua]]s and [[red-throated diver]]s. It was sold to the RSPB by the Hoy Trust for a nominal amount.<ref name=\"haswell-smith\">{{Cite book|last=Haswell-Smith|first=Hamish|title=The Scottish Islands|year=1996|publisher=Canongate|isbn=0-86241-579-9|page=283}}</ref>\n''[[Anastrepta orcadensis]]'',  a [[Marchantiophyta|liverwort]] also known as Orkney Notchwort, was first discovered on Ward Hill by [[William Jackson Hooker]] in 1808.<ref name=RBGE>[http://www.rbge.org.uk/science/cryptogamic-plants-and-fungi/bryology \"Bryology (mosses, liverworts and hornworts)\"] Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh. Retrieved 15 May 2008.</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/stream/annalsofscottish16edin/annalsofscottish16edin_djvu.txt \"West Highland Mosses And Problems They Suggest\"] (January 1907) ''Annals Of Scottish Natural History'' '''61''' p. 46. Edinburgh. Retrieved 11 June 2008.</ref>\n\nThe northern and western parts of Hoy, along with much of the adjoining sea area, is designated as a [[Special Protection Area]]<ref name=sitelink>{{cite web|url=http://gateway.snh.gov.uk/sitelink/searchmap.jsp |title=Sitelink - Map Search |publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|accessdate=2018-01-24}}</ref> due to its importance for nine breeding bird species: [[arctic skua]], [[fulmar]], [[great black-backed gull]], [[great skua]], [[Common murre|guillemot]], [[Black-legged kittiwake]], [[peregrine falcon]], [[Atlantic puffin|puffin]] and [[red-throated diver]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://gateway.snh.gov.uk/sitelink/siteinfo.jsp?pa_code=8513| title=Site Details for Hoy (SPA)|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=2018-03-05|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref> The area is important for its seabird assemblage, which regularly supports 120,000 individual seabirds during the breeding season.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=1902| title=SPA Description (Hoy)|publisher=Joint Nature Conservation Committee|date=2005-07-21|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nHoy is featured prominently in the 1984 video for \"[[Here Comes The Rain Again]]\" by [[Eurythmics]].\n\nHoy also has a performing arts theatre, the Gable End Theatre, which opened in 2000 and has a capacity of 75. The theatre is managed by the Hoy and Walls drama community.\n\nSome rather incongruous [[Art Deco]] structures nearby date from this period. The [[Arts and Crafts Movement|Arts and Crafts]] architect [[William Lethaby]] rebuilt Melsetter house for mountaineer [[Thomas Middlemore]] at the end of the nineteenth century leaving untouched the adjacent barn which is probably mid-18th century.<ref name=\"Tinniswood\">{{cite book|last=Tinniswood|first=Adrian|url=https://books.google.com/books?q=thomas+middlemore++1896++sold+&btnG=Search+Books|title=The Arts & Crafts House|publisher=[[Watson-Guptill Publications]]|year=1999|isbn=0-8230-0364-7|location=New York|pages=34\u201337|authorlink=Adrian Tinniswood}}</ref><ref name=\"Historic Scotland\">{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB48367|desc=Walls (Hoy), Melsetter, The Hall, including Gatepiers to West|cat=B|access-date=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Hoy Cliffs.jpg| Cliffs on the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] coast of Hoy, south of Rackwick\nFile:ScapaFlowVisitorCentreRLH.jpg| Scapa Flow Visitor Centre\nFile:PicHoyHigh.jpg| Hoy High Lighthouse on Graemsay, viewed from Mainland\nFile:Hoy_Orkney_Landesinnere.JPG|Rackwick Valley\nFile:Hoy Orkney Southside.jpg|Rackwick\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Scottish islands}}\n* [[List of islands of Scotland]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hoy}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n*[http://www.hoyorkney.com/ Island of Hoy website launched December 2008]\n*[http://www.readingmountaineeringclub.org.uk/images/Hoy/image5.htm Old Man of Hoy picture gallery]\n\n{{Coord|58|51|N|3|18|W|region:GB_type:isle|display=title}}\n\n{{South West Orkney}}\n{{Orkney Islands}}\n{{Islands of Scotland}}\n{{NSAs in Scotland}}\n{{RSPB sites in Scotland}}\n\n[[Category:Hoy| ]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Orkney Islands]]\n[[Category:Important Bird Areas of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Locations in Norse mythology]]\n[[Category:National scenic areas of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Orkney]]\n[[Category:Royal Society for the Protection of Birds reserves in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hoy"}
{"title_page": "Vaishnavi Dhanraj", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian television and film actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name = Vaishnavi Dhanraj\n| image =  Vaibhavi colors indian telly awards.jpg\n|birth_name = Vaishnavi Bhoyar\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1988|08|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Nagpur]], [[Maharashtra]], India\n| residence = Mumbai, Maharashtra, India\n| occupation = Actress, Model\n| years_active = 2008\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Vaishnavi Dhanraj''' (born 25 August 1988) is an Indian television and film actress. She was the protagonist in ''[[PK Lele A Salesman]]'', an adult Hindi film in the sex comedy genre, in which she played the role of a rich girl called Mary Marlo.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/pk-lele-a-salesman/movie-review/67105315.cms |title=PK Lele A Salesman Movie Review |work=The Times of India |accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> She has also acted as Nirbhaya in ''Satyagraha'' on [[Aaj Tak]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/tv/news-interviews/Vaishnavi-to-recreate-Nirbhaya/articleshow/31660271.cms |title=Vaishnavi to recreate Nirbhaya |work=The Times of India |accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref> Inspector Tasha in [[Sony Entertainment Television]]'s ''[[C.I.D. (Indian TV series) | C.I.D.]]''<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.desitvforum.net/forum/cid-cid-special-bureau/123443-tasha-die-cid.html |title=Vaishnavi Tasha to die in CID |work=The Times of India |accessdate=28 February 2011}}</ref> and Mahi Arora in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Bepannah|Bepannaah]]''. \n\nIn 2011, Vaishnavi wrote several blogs for ''[[The Times of India]]'' as part of the publication's series of celebrity blogs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/vaishnavi-dhanrajs-blog/entry/here-i-am |title=Here I am |date=23 July 2011 |work=The Times of India |accessdate=15 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nVaishnavi was born in [[Nagpur]] and did her schooling from Blind Relief Association's Mundle High School.<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-21/tv/28215839_1_surname-soap-roles New surname has brought me luck: Vaishnavi] ''The Times of India,'' 21 December 2010</ref> After she graduated from Shivaji Science College, her family shifted to [[Kalyan]] in 2008. Vaishnavi's parents encouraged her artistic inclination and escorted her to her initial auditions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj \u2013 Life is all about ups and downs|url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-life-all-about-ups-and-downs |work=Tellychakkar |location=India |date=3 January 2012 |accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref> She was known as '''Vaishnavi Bhoyar''' during her student years.\n\n==Career==\nVaishnavi started her acting career in 2008 with a cameo in ''[[Kasautii Zindagii Kay (2001 TV series)|Kasautii Zindagii Kay]]''.<ref>http://www.tellychakkar.com/video/get-know-vaishnavi-and-simran</ref> Taking note of her work in this show, the production house offered her the parallel lead in ''[[Karam Apnaa Apnaa]]'' in the same year. After acting in these two shows with the name Vaishnavi Bhoyar, she replaced her surname with her father's first name, Dhanraj, due to numerological reasons.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/New-surname-has-brought-me-luck-Vaishnavi/articleshow/7139008.cms |title=Times Of India |author=Elina Priyadarshini Nayak |date=21 December 2010 |accessdate=11 May 2019}}</ref> In 2009, Vaishnavi joined ''[[C.I.D. (Indian TV series) | C.I.D.]]'' as a gun-toting detective named Inspector Tasha. For this show, Vaishnavi refused stunt doubles and performed all her stunts herself. ''CID'' launched her stardom and she became widely popular as Tasha. She was last seen in [[CID (Indian TV series)|CID]] in episode no. 678\n\nHer feisty performance in ''CID'' was instrumental in her winning the main protagonist's role in ''[[Na Aana Is Des Laado (TV series)|Na Aana Is Des Laado]]'' when the show took a time leap of 18 years in December 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/television/na-aana-is-des-laado-to-take-18-year-leap/article1-638628.aspx |title=Na Aana Is Des\u2026Laado to take 18-year leap |work=Hindustan Times |author=Jayeeta Mazumder |date=16 December 2010 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> Vaishnavi played the character of Jhanvi, a feminist who fights for women's empowerment in rural India.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/jhanvi-fight-against-abortion-naa-aana-des-laado |title=Jhanvi to fight against abortion in Naa Aana Is Des Laado |publisher=Tellychakkar |date=6 June 2012 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/interviews/i-am-still-learning-taekwondo-youtube-my-character-vaishnavi-dhanraj |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj |accessdate=28 February 2011 |work=Tellychakkar}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/laado-gets-back-veerpur |title=Laado gets back to Veerpur |date=9 September 2011 |work=Tellychakkar |accessdate=15 April 2014 }}</ref> In early 2012, Vaishnavi contemplated leaving ''Na Aana Is Des Laado'' and rejoining ''CID'' as she was dissatisfied with her role but the issue was settled amicably and she continued being a part of ''Laado'' until it ended in July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-upset-these-days |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj is upset these days |date=19 May 2012 |work=Tellychakkar |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishanvi-dhanraj-quit-laado-get-back-cid |title=Vaishanvi Dhanraj to quit Laado; get back to CID? |date=20 February 2012 |work=Tellychakkar |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> ''Na Aana Is Des Laado'' was based on the issue of [[Female foeticide in India|female foeticide]].\n\nAfter a brief hiatus following her marriage, Vaishnavi returned to television with ''[[Parvarrish \u2013 Kuchh Khattee Kuchh Meethi]]'' on [[Sony Entertainment Television India|Sony T.V]] in May 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/tv/news-interviews/Vaishanavi-Dhanraj-Prashant-Ranyal-to-enter-Parvarrish/articleshow/20259459.cms |title=Vaishanavi Dhanraj & Prashant Ranyal to enter Parvarrish |date=25 May 2013 |work=The Times of India |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> She played the character of Meera Mathur, an immaculate and tranquil businesswoman, which was quite different from her previous roles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-makes-comeback-tv-sony-tvs-parvarrish |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj makes a comeback on TV with Sony TV's Parvarrish |date=1 June 2013 |work=Tellychakkar |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> The show ended in August 2013, following which Vaishnavi was offered the main antagonist's role in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Madhubala \u2013 Ek Ishq Ek Junoon]]''. Her dramatic entry scene in the show featured a stunt sequence in which Vaishnavi walked over a tightrope strung over a busy [[Mumbai]] street.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-enters-rks-life-the-new-girl-madhubala-ek-ishq-ek-junoon |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj enters RK's life as the new girl in Madhubala-Ek Ishq Ek Junoon |publisher=Tellychakkar |date=3 December 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> She played Riya Jaiswal/Devika, a self-obsessed, struggling [[Bollywood]] actress.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://televisionworld.in/vaishnavi-dhanraj-enters-rks-life-girl-madhubala-ek-ishq-ek-junoon/ |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj Enters Rk's Life as the New Girl in Madhubala-ek Ishq Ek Junoon |publisher=Television world |date=3 December 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.onenewspage.com/video/20131204/1522309/Madhubala-Who-is-the-new-girl-in-RK.htm |title=Madhubala: Who is the new girl in RK's life |publisher=onenewspage.com |date=4 December 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> Shortly after her entry, the show took a time leap of a few years, as a result of which Vaishnavi decided to quit the show in January 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/television/tv-show-madhubala-to-take-leap-vivian-d-sena-quits-474535 |title=TV show Madhubala to take leap |publisher=NDTV |agency=Indo-Asian News Service |date=23 January 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.metromasti.com/tv/gossip/Vaishnavi-Sahrawat-aka-Rias-Christmas-plans-post-Madhubala-exit/36235 |title=Vaishnavi Sahrawat aka Ria's christmas plans |publisher=metromasti.com |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nWithin a week of her exiting ''[[Madhubala \u2013 Ek Ishq Ek Junoon]]'', Vaishnavi signed up for [[Star Plus]]'s epic ''[[Mahabharat (2013 TV series)|Mahabharat]]'', her first television show in the mythological genre.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/tv/news-interviews/Not-Pavitra-Punia-but-Vaishnavi-Dhanraj-to-enter-Mahabharat/articleshow/28842525.cms |title=Not Pavitra Punia but Vaishnavi Dhanraj to enter Mahabharat |work=The Times of India |author=Vijaya Tiwari |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> Initially apprehensive about playing the mythical character of [[Hidimbi|Hidimbaa]], she took up the challenge and pulled off a critically acclaimed performance. This character required Vaishnavi to play a double role of an ugly demoness and a stunning enchantress. She later said in an interview that the heavy makeup required for the demoness look took over seven hours to apply, and that the weighty costumes made this shooting schedule one of her most unusual assignments ever.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://forum.punjabijunktion.co.in/f633/vaishnavi-dhanraj-play-bheem-s-wife-mahabharat-444769/ |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj to play Bheem's wife in Mahabharat |publisher=Punjabi Junktion |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://myeduniya.com/Entertainment/TvSerials/?revid=63974/ |title=Madhubala fame Ria aka Vaishnavi Dhanraj as Mahabharat's Hidimba |publisher=myeduniya.com |author=sanchi |date=17 January 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> Her stardom and popularity were furthered through this role.\n\nIn March 2014, Vaishnavi was approached by Indian news channel [[Aaj Tak]] to portray [[Nirbhaya]] in the channel's new social awareness series ''Satyagraha 2014''. Aaj Tak's managing editor Supriya Prasad said that their motive was to create a pioneering show on television, and to trigger social change by bringing back [[Mahatma Gandhi]]'s values of non-violence and the pursuit of truth.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bestmediainfo.com/2014/02/aaj-tak-launches-new-show-satyagraha-2014/ |title=Aaj Tak launches new show 'Satyagraha \u2013 2014' |publisher=bestmediainfo.com |agency=BestMediaInfo Bureau |date=24 February 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.televisionpost.com/television/aaj-tak-launches-series-on-mahatma-gandhi/ |title=Aaj Tak launches series on Mahatma Gandhi |work=Television Post |date=21 February 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> Directed by [[Sunil Manchanda]], this series appealed to the nation's conscience. Vaishnavi later said that this role was the most challenging and humbling experience of her career.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tellytadka.net/vaishnavi-dhanraj-recreate-delhi-gang-rape-victim-nirbhaya-aaj-tak-special-series-satyagrah/ |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj To Recreate Delhi Gang Rape Victim Nirbhaya in Aaj Tak Special Series Satyagrah. |publisher=Tellytadka |author=Vijitha Rajan |date=8 March 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nOver the years Vaishnavi has also acted in episodic shows including ''Kitchen Champion 4'', ''[[India's Got Talent]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bollycurry.com/wallpaper/1280x800/161929-dharamji-shakes-a-leg-with-vaishnavi-dhanraj-on-india-got-talen.htm |title=Dharamji shakes a leg with Vaishnavi Dhanraj on India's Got Talent 3 Grand Finale |publisher=bollycurry.com |author=tellybuzz |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bollycurry.com/wallpaper/1280x800/161927-dharamji-with-rashmi-desai-dipika-samson-and-vaishnavi-dhanraj.htm |title=Dharamji with Rashmi Desai, Dipika Samson and Vaishnavi Dhanraj on India's Got Talent 3 Grand Finale |publisher=bollycurry.com |author=tellybuzz |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> ''[[Crime Patrol (TV series)|Crime Patrol]]'', ''[[Hum Ne Li Hai- Shapath]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://indiandrama.info/vaishnavi-dhanraj-to-play-a-super-villain-in-shapath/ |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj to play a super villain in Shapath |publisher=indiandrama.info |author=Abdul Rehman |date=1 May 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> and ''[[Fear Files]]''.\n\nShe was last seen playing the role of Mahi Arora in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Bepannah|Bepannaah]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 23 December 2012, Vaishnavi married Indian actor and model [[Nitin Sahrawat]] after a year of courtship. The two first met on the set of Nitin's show ''Kitni Mohabbat Hai Season 2''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-dating-actormodel-nitin-sahrawat |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj dating actor/model Nitin Sahrawat |publisher=Tellychakkar |date=1 November 2012 |accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref> The ceremony was conducted in [[Shantikunj]], [[Haridwar]] according to Vedic rituals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-getting-married-23-december |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj getting married on 23 December |work=Tellychakkar |accessdate=13 December 2012}}</ref> The wedding reception in Mumbai was attended by Vaishnavi's friends and co actors from her shows including [[Meghna Malik]], [[Kritika Kamra]], [[Dayanand Shetty]], [[Hrishikesh Pandey]] and [[Simran Kaur]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/events/mumbai/Celebs-attend-actor-model-Nitin-Sahrawats-wedding-reception/articleshow/18076828.cms |title=Celebs attend actor-model Nitin Sahrawat's wedding reception |work=The Times of India |date=18 January 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> For their honeymoon the couple backpacked across [[Western Ghats]] and stayed in a rustic hut on the [[Konkan]] coast for 12 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-enjoying-the-phase-her-life-post-marriage |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj is 'enjoying the phase in her life post marriage' |publisher=Tellychakkar |date=27 April 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> The wedding was included in the list of biggest celebrity weddings of the year by the media.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://idiva.com/photogallery-entertainment/10-biggest-tv-celebrity-weddings-this-year/20184/9 |title=10 Biggest TV Celebrity Weddings This Year |publisher=idiva.com |date=13 March 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014 [[NDTV]] launched a new channel, NDTV Prime.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/photos/news/srk-priyanka-at-the-launch-of-ndtv-prime-india-s-first-2-in-1-channel-17296 |title=SRK, Priyanka at the launch of NDTV Prime \u2013 India's first 2-in-1 channel|publisher=NDTV |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> Nitin and Vaishnavi were the guests for the launch episode of [[NDTV]] Prime's ''The Getaway'', in which the two were given a [[Hyundai Elantra]] which they then drove down to [[Kamshet]]. The theme of this episode being adventure, the couple then paraglided off the challenging Shelar's Site. This episode was shot at their [[Lokhandwala Complex]] home and also featured their pet [[Labrador Retriever]] Thor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/video/player/the-getaway/the-perfect-weekend-getaway-near-mumbai/314090 |title=The perfect weekend getaway near Mumbai |publisher=NDTV |date=21 March 2014 |accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nSahrawat and Dhanraj filed for legal separation in July 2015 and were divorced in January 2016, opting for a mutual and amicable divorce in Bandra family court. Emotional disconnect was cited as the reason for the parting. In December 2016, a Bollywood gossip website alleged that marital abuse was a reason for the divorce.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.spotboye.com/television/tv-interviews/tv-actress-vaishnavi-dhanraj-says-her-husband-beat-her-up-until-her-leg-bled/58458ebdaa06626027f19d0f|title=TV Actress Vaishnavi Dhanraj Says Her Husband Beat Her Up Until Her Leg Bled! |last=Lalwani |first=Vickey |work=SPOTBOYE |date=6 December 2016 |accessdate=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n==Filmography==\n===Films===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"24:95%;\"\n|-  style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Film !! Role \n|-\n| 2018\n|''[[Vodka Diaries]]''             \nAnanya\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[PK Lele A Salesman]]''\n| Mary Marlo<ref>{{cite news |url=https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/pk-lele-a-salesman/movie-review/67105315.cms |title=PK Lele A Salesman Movie Review |work=The Times of India |accessdate=21 January 2019 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"24:95%;\"\n|-  style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Show !! Role \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2008 || ''[[Kasautii Zindagii Kay (2001 TV series)|Kasautii Zindagii Kay]]'' || \n|-\n| ''[[Karam Apnaa Apnaa]]'' || Aastha Vivan Kapoor\n|-\n| 2009-2010 || ''[[C.I.D. (Indian TV series) | C.I.D.]]'' || Inspector Tasha Kumar\n|-\n| 2010-12 || ''[[Na Aana Is Des Laado]]'' || Jhanvi \n|-\n| 2011 ||''Kitchen Champion 4'' || Contestant\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2012 || rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[Crime Patrol (TV series)|Crime Patrol]]''|| Nisha\n|-\n| Renu Gawde\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2013 || ''[[Hum Ne Li Hai- Shapath]]'' || Nayantara/Sakuna \n|-\n|''[[Parvarrish \u2013 Kuchh Khattee Kuchh Meethi|Parvarrish\u2013Kuchh Khattee Kuchh Meethi]]'' || Mrs. Mathur \n|-\n|''[[Madhubala - Ek Ishq Ek Junoon|Madhubala-Ek Ishq Ek Junoon]]'' || Riya \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2014 || ''[[Mahabharat (2013 TV series)|Mahabharat]]'' || Hidimbaa\n|-\n|''Satyagraha''|| [[Nirbhaya]] \n|-\n|''The Getaway''|| Herself \n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Begusarai (TV series)|Begusarai]]''|| Maya \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2016 || ''Beti Ka Farz'' || Avantika \n|-\n|''[[Sasural Simar Ka]]''|| Kamya\n|-\n|''[[Yeh Vaada Raha (TV series)|Yeh Vaada Raha]]'' || Icchha\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Beyhadh]]'' || Pooja \n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Bepannaah]]''|| Mahi Arora \n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Navrangi Re!]]'' || Chitralekha\n|-\n|- 2020 || ''[Yeh Teri Galiyan]]'' || TBA\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Vaishnavi Dhanraj}}\n* {{IMDb name|4480587}}\n*{{Instagram|vaishnavidhanraj}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dhanraj, Vaishnavi}}\n[[Category:Indian television actresses]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Marathi people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Nagpur]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi television]]\n`\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian television and film actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name = Vaishnavi Dhanraj\n| image =  Vaibhavi colors indian telly awards.jpg\n|birth_name = Vaishnavi Bhoyar\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1988|08|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Nagpur]], [[Maharashtra]], India\n| residence = Mumbai, Maharashtra, India\n| occupation = Actress, Model\n| years_active = 2008\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Vaishnavi Dhanraj''' (born 25 August 1988) is an Indian television and film actress. She was the protagonist in ''[[PK Lele A Salesman]]'', an adult Hindi film in the sex comedy genre, in which she played the role of a rich girl called Mary Marlo.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/pk-lele-a-salesman/movie-review/67105315.cms |title=PK Lele A Salesman Movie Review |work=The Times of India |accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> She has also acted as Nirbhaya in ''Satyagraha'' on [[Aaj Tak]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/tv/news-interviews/Vaishnavi-to-recreate-Nirbhaya/articleshow/31660271.cms |title=Vaishnavi to recreate Nirbhaya |work=The Times of India |accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref> Inspector Tasha in [[Sony Entertainment Television]]'s ''[[C.I.D. (Indian TV series) | C.I.D.]]''<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.desitvforum.net/forum/cid-cid-special-bureau/123443-tasha-die-cid.html |title=Vaishnavi Tasha to die in CID |work=The Times of India |accessdate=28 February 2011}}</ref> and Mahi Arora in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Bepannah|Bepannaah]]''. \n\nIn 2011, Vaishnavi wrote several blogs for ''[[The Times of India]]'' as part of the publication's series of celebrity blogs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/vaishnavi-dhanrajs-blog/entry/here-i-am |title=Here I am |date=23 July 2011 |work=The Times of India |accessdate=15 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nVaishnavi was born in [[Nagpur]] and did her schooling from Blind Relief Association's Mundle High School.<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-21/tv/28215839_1_surname-soap-roles New surname has brought me luck: Vaishnavi] ''The Times of India,'' 21 December 2010</ref> After she graduated from Shivaji Science College, her family shifted to [[Kalyan]] in 2008. Vaishnavi's parents encouraged her artistic inclination and escorted her to her initial auditions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj \u2013 Life is all about ups and downs|url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-life-all-about-ups-and-downs |work=Tellychakkar |location=India |date=3 January 2012 |accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref> She was known as '''Vaishnavi Bhoyar''' during her student years.\n\n==Career==\nVaishnavi started her acting career in 2008 with a cameo in ''[[Kasautii Zindagii Kay (2001 TV series)|Kasautii Zindagii Kay]]''.<ref>http://www.tellychakkar.com/video/get-know-vaishnavi-and-simran</ref> Taking note of her work in this show, the production house offered her the parallel lead in ''[[Karam Apnaa Apnaa]]'' in the same year. After acting in these two shows with the name Vaishnavi Bhoyar, she replaced her surname with her father's first name, Dhanraj, due to numerological reasons.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/New-surname-has-brought-me-luck-Vaishnavi/articleshow/7139008.cms |title=Times Of India |author=Elina Priyadarshini Nayak |date=21 December 2010 |accessdate=11 May 2019}}</ref> In 2009, Vaishnavi joined ''[[C.I.D. (Indian TV series) | C.I.D.]]'' as a gun-toting detective named Inspector Tasha. For this show, Vaishnavi refused stunt doubles and performed all her stunts herself. ''CID'' launched her stardom and she became widely popular as Tasha. She was last seen in [[CID]] in episode no. 678\n\nHer feisty performance in ''CID'' was instrumental in her winning the main protagonist's role in ''[[Na Aana Is Des Laado (TV series)|Na Aana Is Des Laado]]'' when the show took a time leap of 18 years in December 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/television/na-aana-is-des-laado-to-take-18-year-leap/article1-638628.aspx |title=Na Aana Is Des\u2026Laado to take 18-year leap |work=Hindustan Times |author=Jayeeta Mazumder |date=16 December 2010 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> Vaishnavi played the character of Jhanvi, a feminist who fights for women's empowerment in rural India.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/jhanvi-fight-against-abortion-naa-aana-des-laado |title=Jhanvi to fight against abortion in Naa Aana Is Des Laado |publisher=Tellychakkar |date=6 June 2012 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/interviews/i-am-still-learning-taekwondo-youtube-my-character-vaishnavi-dhanraj |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj |accessdate=28 February 2011 |work=Tellychakkar}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/laado-gets-back-veerpur |title=Laado gets back to Veerpur |date=9 September 2011 |work=Tellychakkar |accessdate=15 April 2014 }}</ref> In early 2012, Vaishnavi contemplated leaving ''Na Aana Is Des Laado'' and rejoining ''CID'' as she was dissatisfied with her role but the issue was settled amicably and she continued being a part of ''Laado'' until it ended in July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-upset-these-days |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj is upset these days |date=19 May 2012 |work=Tellychakkar |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishanvi-dhanraj-quit-laado-get-back-cid |title=Vaishanvi Dhanraj to quit Laado; get back to CID? |date=20 February 2012 |work=Tellychakkar |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> ''Na Aana Is Des Laado'' was based on the issue of [[Female foeticide in India|female foeticide]].\n\nAfter a brief hiatus following her marriage, Vaishnavi returned to television with ''[[Parvarrish \u2013 Kuchh Khattee Kuchh Meethi]]'' on [[Sony Entertainment Television India|Sony T.V]] in May 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/tv/news-interviews/Vaishanavi-Dhanraj-Prashant-Ranyal-to-enter-Parvarrish/articleshow/20259459.cms |title=Vaishanavi Dhanraj & Prashant Ranyal to enter Parvarrish |date=25 May 2013 |work=The Times of India |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> She played the character of Meera Mathur, an immaculate and tranquil businesswoman, which was quite different from her previous roles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-makes-comeback-tv-sony-tvs-parvarrish |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj makes a comeback on TV with Sony TV's Parvarrish |date=1 June 2013 |work=Tellychakkar |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> The show ended in August 2013, following which Vaishnavi was offered the main antagonist's role in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Madhubala \u2013 Ek Ishq Ek Junoon]]''. Her dramatic entry scene in the show featured a stunt sequence in which Vaishnavi walked over a tightrope strung over a busy [[Mumbai]] street.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-enters-rks-life-the-new-girl-madhubala-ek-ishq-ek-junoon |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj enters RK's life as the new girl in Madhubala-Ek Ishq Ek Junoon |publisher=Tellychakkar |date=3 December 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> She played Riya Jaiswal/Devika, a self-obsessed, struggling [[Bollywood]] actress.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://televisionworld.in/vaishnavi-dhanraj-enters-rks-life-girl-madhubala-ek-ishq-ek-junoon/ |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj Enters Rk's Life as the New Girl in Madhubala-ek Ishq Ek Junoon |publisher=Television world |date=3 December 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.onenewspage.com/video/20131204/1522309/Madhubala-Who-is-the-new-girl-in-RK.htm |title=Madhubala: Who is the new girl in RK's life |publisher=onenewspage.com |date=4 December 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> Shortly after her entry, the show took a time leap of a few years, as a result of which Vaishnavi decided to quit the show in January 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/television/tv-show-madhubala-to-take-leap-vivian-d-sena-quits-474535 |title=TV show Madhubala to take leap |publisher=NDTV |agency=Indo-Asian News Service |date=23 January 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.metromasti.com/tv/gossip/Vaishnavi-Sahrawat-aka-Rias-Christmas-plans-post-Madhubala-exit/36235 |title=Vaishnavi Sahrawat aka Ria's christmas plans |publisher=metromasti.com |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nWithin a week of her exiting ''[[Madhubala \u2013 Ek Ishq Ek Junoon]]'', Vaishnavi signed up for [[Star Plus]]'s epic ''[[Mahabharat (2013 TV series)|Mahabharat]]'', her first television show in the mythological genre.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/tv/news-interviews/Not-Pavitra-Punia-but-Vaishnavi-Dhanraj-to-enter-Mahabharat/articleshow/28842525.cms |title=Not Pavitra Punia but Vaishnavi Dhanraj to enter Mahabharat |work=The Times of India |author=Vijaya Tiwari |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> Initially apprehensive about playing the mythical character of [[Hidimbi|Hidimbaa]], she took up the challenge and pulled off a critically acclaimed performance. This character required Vaishnavi to play a double role of an ugly demoness and a stunning enchantress. She later said in an interview that the heavy makeup required for the demoness look took over seven hours to apply, and that the weighty costumes made this shooting schedule one of her most unusual assignments ever.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://forum.punjabijunktion.co.in/f633/vaishnavi-dhanraj-play-bheem-s-wife-mahabharat-444769/ |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj to play Bheem's wife in Mahabharat |publisher=Punjabi Junktion |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://myeduniya.com/Entertainment/TvSerials/?revid=63974/ |title=Madhubala fame Ria aka Vaishnavi Dhanraj as Mahabharat's Hidimba |publisher=myeduniya.com |author=sanchi |date=17 January 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> Her stardom and popularity were furthered through this role.\n\nIn March 2014, Vaishnavi was approached by Indian news channel [[Aaj Tak]] to portray [[Nirbhaya]] in the channel's new social awareness series ''Satyagraha 2014''. Aaj Tak's managing editor Supriya Prasad said that their motive was to create a pioneering show on television, and to trigger social change by bringing back [[Mahatma Gandhi]]'s values of non-violence and the pursuit of truth.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bestmediainfo.com/2014/02/aaj-tak-launches-new-show-satyagraha-2014/ |title=Aaj Tak launches new show 'Satyagraha \u2013 2014' |publisher=bestmediainfo.com |agency=BestMediaInfo Bureau |date=24 February 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.televisionpost.com/television/aaj-tak-launches-series-on-mahatma-gandhi/ |title=Aaj Tak launches series on Mahatma Gandhi |work=Television Post |date=21 February 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> Directed by [[Sunil Manchanda]], this series appealed to the nation's conscience. Vaishnavi later said that this role was the most challenging and humbling experience of her career.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tellytadka.net/vaishnavi-dhanraj-recreate-delhi-gang-rape-victim-nirbhaya-aaj-tak-special-series-satyagrah/ |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj To Recreate Delhi Gang Rape Victim Nirbhaya in Aaj Tak Special Series Satyagrah. |publisher=Tellytadka |author=Vijitha Rajan |date=8 March 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nOver the years Vaishnavi has also acted in episodic shows including ''Kitchen Champion 4'', ''[[India's Got Talent]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bollycurry.com/wallpaper/1280x800/161929-dharamji-shakes-a-leg-with-vaishnavi-dhanraj-on-india-got-talen.htm |title=Dharamji shakes a leg with Vaishnavi Dhanraj on India's Got Talent 3 Grand Finale |publisher=bollycurry.com |author=tellybuzz |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bollycurry.com/wallpaper/1280x800/161927-dharamji-with-rashmi-desai-dipika-samson-and-vaishnavi-dhanraj.htm |title=Dharamji with Rashmi Desai, Dipika Samson and Vaishnavi Dhanraj on India's Got Talent 3 Grand Finale |publisher=bollycurry.com |author=tellybuzz |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> ''[[Crime Patrol (TV series)|Crime Patrol]]'', ''[[Hum Ne Li Hai- Shapath]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://indiandrama.info/vaishnavi-dhanraj-to-play-a-super-villain-in-shapath/ |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj to play a super villain in Shapath |publisher=indiandrama.info |author=Abdul Rehman |date=1 May 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> and ''[[Fear Files]]''.\n\nShe was last seen playing the role of Mahi Arora in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Bepannah|Bepannaah]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 23 December 2012, Vaishnavi married Indian actor and model [[Nitin Sahrawat]] after a year of courtship. The two first met on the set of Nitin's show ''Kitni Mohabbat Hai Season 2''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-dating-actormodel-nitin-sahrawat |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj dating actor/model Nitin Sahrawat |publisher=Tellychakkar |date=1 November 2012 |accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref> The ceremony was conducted in [[Shantikunj]], [[Haridwar]] according to Vedic rituals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-getting-married-23-december |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj getting married on 23 December |work=Tellychakkar |accessdate=13 December 2012}}</ref> The wedding reception in Mumbai was attended by Vaishnavi's friends and co actors from her shows including [[Meghna Malik]], [[Kritika Kamra]], [[Dayanand Shetty]], [[Hrishikesh Pandey]] and [[Simran Kaur]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/events/mumbai/Celebs-attend-actor-model-Nitin-Sahrawats-wedding-reception/articleshow/18076828.cms |title=Celebs attend actor-model Nitin Sahrawat's wedding reception |work=The Times of India |date=18 January 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> For their honeymoon the couple backpacked across [[Western Ghats]] and stayed in a rustic hut on the [[Konkan]] coast for 12 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/vaishnavi-dhanraj-enjoying-the-phase-her-life-post-marriage |title=Vaishnavi Dhanraj is 'enjoying the phase in her life post marriage' |publisher=Tellychakkar |date=27 April 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> The wedding was included in the list of biggest celebrity weddings of the year by the media.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://idiva.com/photogallery-entertainment/10-biggest-tv-celebrity-weddings-this-year/20184/9 |title=10 Biggest TV Celebrity Weddings This Year |publisher=idiva.com |date=13 March 2013 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014 [[NDTV]] launched a new channel, NDTV Prime.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/photos/news/srk-priyanka-at-the-launch-of-ndtv-prime-india-s-first-2-in-1-channel-17296 |title=SRK, Priyanka at the launch of NDTV Prime \u2013 India's first 2-in-1 channel|publisher=NDTV |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> Nitin and Vaishnavi were the guests for the launch episode of [[NDTV]] Prime's ''The Getaway'', in which the two were given a [[Hyundai Elantra]] which they then drove down to [[Kamshet]]. The theme of this episode being adventure, the couple then paraglided off the challenging Shelar's Site. This episode was shot at their [[Lokhandwala Complex]] home and also featured their pet [[Labrador Retriever]] Thor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/video/player/the-getaway/the-perfect-weekend-getaway-near-mumbai/314090 |title=The perfect weekend getaway near Mumbai |publisher=NDTV |date=21 March 2014 |accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nSahrawat and Dhanraj filed for legal separation in July 2015 and were divorced in January 2016, opting for a mutual and amicable divorce in Bandra family court. Emotional disconnect was cited as the reason for the parting. In December 2016, a Bollywood gossip website alleged that marital abuse was a reason for the divorce.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.spotboye.com/television/tv-interviews/tv-actress-vaishnavi-dhanraj-says-her-husband-beat-her-up-until-her-leg-bled/58458ebdaa06626027f19d0f|title=TV Actress Vaishnavi Dhanraj Says Her Husband Beat Her Up Until Her Leg Bled! |last=Lalwani |first=Vickey |work=SPOTBOYE |date=6 December 2016 |accessdate=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n==Filmography==\n===Films===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"24:95%;\"\n|-  style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Film !! Role \n|-\n| 2018\n|''[[Vodka Diaries]]''             \nAnanya\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[PK Lele A Salesman]]