{"title_page": "MTV (Southeast Asian TV channel)", "text_new": "{{moresources|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox television channel\n| name = MTV Asia\n| other names = \n| logofile = MTV Logo 2010.svg\n| logosize = 150px\n| launch = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1991|09|15}} (original)<br>{{Start date and age|df=yes|1995|05|03}} (relaunch)\n| closed date = {{End date and age|df=yes|1994|04|30}} (original)\n| country = [[Hong Kong]] (1991-94)<br>[[Singapore]] (1995-present)\n| broadcast area = [[Southeast Asia]]\n| headquarters = [[Hong Kong]] (1991-1994)<br>[[Singapore]] (1995-present)\n| former names = \n| replaced names = \n| replaced by names = [[Channel V]] (original)\n| picture format = [[1080i]] [[HDTV]]<br>{{small|(downscaled to [[16:9]] [[480i]]/[[576i]] for the [[SDTV]] feed)}}\n| owner = [[Fox Networks Group Asia Pacific|STAR TV]] and [[Viacom (1952\u20132006)|Viacom]] (1991-1994)<br>[[ViacomCBS Networks EMEAA]] (1995-present)\n| web = {{url|mtvasia.com}}\n| sister names = [[Nickelodeon (Southeast Asian TV channel)|Nickelodeon]]<br>[[Comedy Central (Southeast Asian TV channel)|Comedy Central]]<br>[[Nick Jr. (Southeast Asian TV channel)|Nick Jr.]]<br>[[Paramount Channel]]<br>[[MTV Live HD]]\n| sat serv 1 = [[BiG TV (Indonesia)|BiG TV]]\n| sat chan 1 = Channel 257\n| sat serv 2 = [[Astro (Malaysian satellite television)|Astro]]\n| sat chan 2 = Channel 718 (SD)\n| sat serv 3 = [[Sky Pacific]]\n| sat chan 3 = Channel 4\n| sat serv 4 = [[Sky Net]] <br> (Myanmar)\n| sat chan 4 = Channel 52\n| sat serv 5 = CANAL+ <br>(Myanmar)\n| sat chan 5 = Channel 74\n| sat serv 6 = [[Kristal-Astro]]\n| sat chan 6 = Channel 718 (SD)\n| sat serv 7 = [[:id:Skynindo|Skynindo]]<br>(Indonesia)\n| sat chan 7 = Channel 41 (HD 800/77/99)<br>Channel 23 (C01/C02)\n| sat serv 8 = [[Cignal]] <br> (Philippines)\n| sat chan 8 = Channel 151 \n| sat serv 9 = SatLite <br> (Philippines)\n| sat chan 9 = Channel 110\n| cable serv 1 = [[First Media]] <br> (Indonesia)\n| cable chan 1 = Channel 220 (SD)<br>Channel 356 (HD)\n| cable serv 2 = South Luzon CATV <br> (Philippines)\n| cable chan 2 = Channel 321 (Digital)\n| cable serv 3 = [[Macau CATV]] (Macau)\n| cable chan 3 = Channel 446\n| cable serv 4 = [[SkyCable]] <br> (Philippines)\n| cable chan 4 = Channel 71 \n| cable serv 5 = [[Cablelink]] <br> (Philippines)\n| cable chan 5 = Channel 42\n| cable serv 6 = [[Destiny Cable]] <br> (Philippines)\n| cable chan 6 = Channel 71 (Digital)\n| cable serv 7 = [[Parasat Cable TV]] <br> (Philippines) \n| cable chan 7 = Channel 26\n| cable serv 8 = Fil Products Ozamiz <br> (Philippines)\n| cable chan 8 = Channel 78\n| iptv serv 1 = [[IndosatM2]] <br> (Indonesia)\n| iptv chan 1 = Channel 152\n| iptv serv 2 = [[M2V Mobile TV]]\n| iptv chan 2 = Channel 0003\n| iptv serv 3 = [[Singtel TV]] <br> (Singapore)\n| iptv chan 3 = Channel 350 (HD)\n| iptv serv 4 = [[StarHub TV]] <br> (Singapore)\n| iptv chan 4 = Channel 533\n| iptv serv 5 = [[Unifi TV]] <br> (Malaysia)\n| iptv chan 5 = Channel 602 (old) <br> Channel 531 (new) (HD)\n\n}}\n'''MTV''' is an Asian music pay-television channel that was originally launched on 15 September 1991 as a music channel exclusively on [[Fox Networks Group Asia Pacific|STAR TV]], and then on 3 May 1995 as a standalone pay TV channel. It is owned by [[ViacomCBS Networks EMEAA]].\n\n==History==\nMTV Asia was launched on 15 September 1991, a joint venture between STAR TV and [[Viacom (original)|Viacom]], but later STAR TV's contract with MTV expired on 30 April 1994. This led to the birth of [[Channel V|Channel [V]]].\n\nMTV Mandarin launched as a 24-hour Chinese language channel in [[Hong Kong]] serving Mandarin-speaking [[China]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Macau]], [[Taiwan]], and [[Singapore]] on 25 April 1995.\n\nMTV Southeast Asia launched on 3 May 1995 as an English-language channel seen throughout Asia in territories including [[Brunei]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Indonesia]], [[Macau]], [[Malaysia]], [[Papua New Guinea]], the [[Philippines]], [[Singapore]], [[Thailand]], and [[Vietnam]].\n\nMTV partners with domestic media companies to produce local-language content for its channels in [[Indonesia]], [[Philippines]], [[Thailand]], and [[Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mediabusinessasia.com/article.php?id=541|title=Options Open and Close For Viacom|last=Haskins|first=Will|date=27 June 2014|work=Media Business Asia|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==VJs==\n{{main|List of MTV VJs}}\n\n==Current programs==\n===Music Video===\n*MTV Hits\n*MTV Musika\n*K-Wave\n*OK Karaoke\n*Chart Attack\n*MTV Now Streaming\n*Yo! Hip-Hop Hits\n\n===Concert/Acoustic===\n*MTV World Stage\n*The Show\n*MTV Jammin'\n\n===Variety Show===\n*[[A Double Shot at Love]]\n*[[OK Danceoke]]\n*[[Ghosted: Love Gone Missing]]\n*[[Usavich]]\n*[[Wild 'N Out]]\n*[[MTV's Bugging Out]]\n*[[Fear Factor]]\n*[[Just Tattoo of Us USA]]\n*[[Catfish: The TV Show]]\n*[[MTV Asks]]\n*[[Ridiculousness (TV series)|Ridiculousness]]\n*[[Vidiots]]\n*[[Idol Battle Cook]]\n*[[Disaster Date]]\n*[[Friendzone]]\n*[[My Super Sweet 16]]\n\n==Past programs==\n*[[List of programmes broadcast by MTV in Asia]]\n*[[List of programs broadcast by MTV]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[MTV]]\n*[[MTV Networks Asia Pacific]]\n*[[MTV Mandarin]] (1995\u20132003, split)\n**MTV Taiwan (2003\u2013ongoing)\n**MTV China (2003\u2013ongoing)\n*[[MTV India]] (1996\u2013ongoing)\n*[[MTV Korea]] (2001\u2013ongoing)\n*[[MTV Pakistan]] (2006\u20132011, defunct)\n*[[MTV Vietnam]] (2011\u2013ongoing)\n*[[MTV Thailand]] (2001\u20132011, 2013\u20132016, defunct)\n*[[MTV Philippines]] (1992\u20132010, defunct)\n*[[MTV Pinoy]] (2014\u20132016, 2017, defunct)\n*[[MTV Indonesia]] (1993\u20132001, 2002\u20132011, 2014\u20132015, defunct)\n** [[antv]] (1993-2001)\n** [[Global TV]] (2002-2011)\n** [[RCTI]] (2015)\n** [[RTV (Indonesia)|RTV]] (2014-2015)\n** [[CTV Network|CTV Banten]] (2015)\n*[[MTVph]] (2017-2018, defunct)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Star TV}}\n{{MTV Networks}}\n{{Viacom}